<HEADLINE> Bio-Safety Guidelines Streamline Genetic Research in Bangladesh: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's research activities in
the field of biotechnology entered into a new phase as Science
Ministry had endorsed "Bio-safety Guidelines" to boost ingenuous
endeavors in genetics, experts said at a lecture conference
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Fresh efforts are in the take-off stage following creation of
the new guidelines for streamlining research on genetically
modified organism, researchers said at the conference hosted by
the Science Museum as part of its annual popular science discourse.
</P>
<P>
Bio-technologist Professor Syed Hadiuzzaman of Dhaka University
said the bio-safety guideline of Bangladesh would serve as
protective shield against unscrupulous research with transgenic
plants or bacteria popularly known as genetically modified
organism.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Human Genome Project, he said the scientists have
discovered the secret map of life and this would create huge
impact on the future medicine and pharmacology.
</P>
<P>
Science Minister Noor Uddin Khan said the government is aware
of the impact of innovations in the field of life science and the
authorities would place bio-safety guidelines before parliament
for legislative endorsement.
</P>
<P>
The proposed National Institute of Biotechnology (NIB) in Savar,
a suburb of Dhaka, will add further impetus to the
biotechnological research in the country, the minister said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
