<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors Promise Zambia 1 Billion Dollars for Poverty Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Donors including the World Bank
Tuesday promised to provide Zambia with slightly over one billion
U.S. dollars within one year in support of the country's economic
reform and poverty reduction programs.
</P>
<P>
They made the promise at the end of the three-day 12th
Consultative Group meeting, the first ever here in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The meeting attended by 25 bilateral and multilateral agencies
discussed the country's economic reform and poverty reduction
programs.
</P>
<P>
The discussions focused on the issues including public
expenditure priorities and management, political governance, HIV/
AIDS, diversification of the economy, Zambia's high debt burden,
and most importantly the need to focus development efforts on
poverty reduction and homegrown development strategies.
</P>
<P>
The meeting stressed the need for the country and its
cooperating partners to work toward expeditious access of Zambia
to debt relief under the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC)
initiative.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by delegations from Belgium, Britain,
Canada, Denmark, Finland, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Japan,
the Netherlands, Norway, Sweden, the United States, the African
Development Bank, the Arab Bank for Economic Development in Africa,
the European Commission, the European Investment Bank, the Food
and Agriculture Organization, the International Monetary Fund, the
Saudi Fund for Development, the United Nations Children's Fund,
the U.N. Development Program, the World Bank Group, and the World
Food Program.
</P>
<P>
Zambian government ministers, parliament members and
representatives of civil societies also attended the meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
