<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Executive and Legislative in Efforts toward Rapprochement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
and House Speaker Ghali Umar Na'Abba held a closed-door meeting
Monday to patch the much troubled ties between the executive and
legislative branch of the west African nation's government.
</P>
<P>
The President was said to have vehemently dismissed allegations
that he was bent on disrupting the House leadership by helping a
come-back of the resigned former house speaker Salisu Buhari,
reported Nigerian press on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There were reportedly pleas from both parties at the meeting to
sink their differences whereupon they promised to respect the
principles of separation of powers and work toward the promotion
of democracy.
</P>
<P>
In another unusual approach toward rapprochement, President
Olusegun Obasanjo Monday commissioned the Senate President Chuba
Okadigbo's capital residence.
</P>
<P>
"Let there be harmony among all the realms of government, with
mutual respect and tolerance as our guides and with the common aim
of providing good governance in a free society, where prosperity
and happiness will reign", said Okadigbo at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The two branches of government had often been found at odds
since the returning into power of the civilian government last
year. Since then, Obasanjo often criticizes the top legislature of
low efficiency and selfishness, resulting in the delays of coming
into effect of important laws, the legislature trading words back
by accusing the president of acting in a totalitarian style like
former military rulers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
