<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tetanus Kills 34,600 Nigerian Infants Yearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Tetanus still causes about 34,600
infant deaths in Nigeria yearly, UN Children's Fund (UNICEF) said
in its report, which became available Tuesday to Xinhua here.
</P>
<P>
Tetanus attacks new-born babies through unsanitary birth
practices, including the cutting of umbilical chord with unclean
blade.
</P>
<P>
According to the UNICEF report, Nigeria has the second highest
figure of infant deaths caused by neonatal tetanus, with India
topping the list with 48,600. Pakistan is placed the third.
</P>
<P>
It said the figures for the first three countries on the list
accounted for more than half of the world's neonatal tetanus
deaths, an "entirely preventable" disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
