<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Conservative GC Pledges Cooperation with Majlis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative Guardians
Council (GC) pledged on Wednesday to cooperate with the sixth
Majlis (parliament) which is dominated by reformers supporting
President Mohammad Khatami's liberal policies.
</P>
<P>
GC members had already voiced their support for the Majlis in
their meeting with speaker Mehdi Karrubi and the two bodies will
work together for the development of the country, spokesman of the
12-member body Ayatollah Reza Ostadi said.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a meeting between GC members and Majlis
speaker Karrubi early this month, in which both sides called for "
understanding and coordination."
</P>
<P>
Ostadi dismissed allegations that the GC had acted in a biased
manner in its supervision of the parliamentary elections in
February, saying the council would not be swayed by the wishes of
any particular (political) faction.
</P>
<P>
February's elections resulted in a landslide victory for
reformers, who seized control of the legislative body after years
of conservative dominance. But the conservative GC, supervisor of
the elections, had gone out of its way to prevent reformers from
taking over the Majlis smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Citing vote-rigging in the election process, the council
annulled balloting results in a number of constituencies, in some
cases even directly transferring the seats of reformist winners to
their conservative opponents.
</P>
<P>
Although the new Majlis managed to start work on May 27, many
people believe that it will face many obstacles in pushing through
the country's reformist programs advocated by Khatami since 1997.
</P>
<P>
All bills passed by the Majlis have to be approved by the GC
before they become law. And if there is any conflict between the
two bodies, a third body, the State Expediency Council (SEC), will
act as the arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
The SEC is headed by former President Hashemi Rafsanjani, a
moderate believed to be close to the conservatives. Rafsanjani had
taken part in the February elections and managed to win a seat in
the new Majlis, but quitted the seat after being accused of
receiving help from the GC, the election watchdog. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
