<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian, U.S. Presidents Discuss Palestinian-Israeli Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
received a telephone call from United States President Bill Clinton
Wednesday night on the ongoing negotiations between the
Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
During the conversation, Clinton briefed Mubarak on the
Palestinian-Israeli talks under way at the Camp David presidential
retreat near the U.S. capital of Washington, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also exchanged views on the contentious issues
between the two sides, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Since July 11, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak, hosted by Clinton, have been negotiating
final solutions to the thorniest issues including the final borders
of the future Palestinian state, the status of Jerusalem, the fate
of Palestinian refugees and Jewish settlers in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The summit has entered a make-or-break stage as President
Clinton is preparing to leave for Japan to attend a Group of Eight
summit. Clinton had planned to depart on Wednesday, but he latered
postponed by 24 hours to give peace efforts one last try.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Barak was reported to be preparing to go
home after concluding that "the Palestinians are not a true partner
for peace." White House spokesman Joe Lockhart confirmed later
that the discussions were continuing.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to make peace with Israel, plays
an active role in mediating the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspended Egyptian Islamist Party, Newspaper Face Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's socialist public prosecutor
on Wednesday filed nine charges against leaders of the suspended
Islamist Labor Party and its newspaper Al-Shaab that could land the
defendants in jail for up to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Party leader Ibrahim Shukri, secretary-general Abel Hussein and
Al-Shaab editor-in-chief Magdi Hussein are accused of having links
with the banned fundamentalist Muslim Brotherhood and members of
other Islamic extremist groups, prosecutor Gaber Rihan said.
</P>
<P>
Magdi Hussein has been serving a two-year prison term since
April for defaming Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of
Agriculture and Land Reclamation Youssef Amin Wali.
</P>
<P>
The bi-weekly Al-Shaab offered a platform to Muslim Brotherhood
and other Islamist groups to spread incitement and propagate their
tenets, Rihan was quoted as saying by Egypt's Middle East News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The defendants are also accused of changing the orientation and
the emblem of the party, turning it into an Islamist party without
notifying the country's Political Parties Committee, which
regulates party activities, changes introduced to the internal
structure of the party, particularly its name and conditions for
joining.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1979, the party was originally called the Socialist
Labor Party. In 1987, it formed an electoral coalition with the
Muslim Brotherhood and two years later adopted an Islamist
political line.
</P>
<P>
The party officials were also accused of not informing the
parties committee of meetings held by its leader and officials with
foreign groups and political organizations, Rihan said.
</P>
<P>
The defendants asked for donation from citizens without the
authorization of the Social Affairs Ministry, and they also failed
to declare some of their sources of financing and donors' names and
prepare an annual party and newspaper budget, he added.
</P>
<P>
The defendants face sentences of between three and 15 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
The parties committee, which includes figures close to the
government, suspended the party and newspaper in May, citing
divisions in the party. The suspension came before Egypt's
parliamentary elections, expected in November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 17 Elderly Costa Ricans Die in Asylum Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The asylum is situated 190 kilometers northwest of San Jose,
said Red Cross and Judicial Investigations Organization (OIJ)
sources on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Red Cross official Walter Zarate told Xinhua that it was the
Tilaran Home for the Elderly, an asylum managed by a national
association that housed a number of old people.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the fire has not been determined, but police
sources said that it could have been caused by a short circuit in
a television set.
</P>
<P>
The judicial authorities are investigating the possibility of a
fire caused on purpose, but so far that hypothesis has no ground.
"There are no circumstances that could point to a fire started by
arsonists," said the OIJ director Lineth Saborio.
</P>
<P>
The fire spread rapidly for the strong winds dominating in that
area. The main Fire Department station is located in the city of
Canas, 22 kilometers from Tilaran, which delayed the assistance to
the old persons.
</P>
<P>
The death of the 17 persons and the injuries suffered by 24
more were attributed to the fact that only two persons were in
charge of the asylum management, and to the situation of the old
people who had difficulty to move without assistance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
