<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Frost in Brazil Raises Colombian Coffee Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Freezing weather that affected the
coffee harvest in Brazil has caused a rise in the price of the
Colombian grain, Coffee Raisers National Federation (FNC) manager
Jorge Cardenas said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian coffee internal quotation rose 17 percent, from
164.2 dollars to 192.2 dollars for a 125-kilo bag, Cardenas told
the press.
</P>
<P>
A cold wave from the Antarctic affected last week the coffee
plantations in the states of Parana and Sao Paulo, in the south of
Brazil, and Monday those of Minas Gerais, the biggest coffee
producer.
</P>
<P>
The temperature drop in Brazil, the biggest coffee producer in
the world, became "a lifesaver" for the depressed Colombian coffee
sector, added Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
The prices of Colombian coffee in the international markets,
which was 0.82 U.S. dollars per pound two weeks ago, jumped
Tuesday to 1.21 dollars because of the nervousness of the market
after the frost in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The frost in Brazil was not as intense as others that have
destroyed up to 10 million 70 kilo bags, producers said.
</P>
<P>
Colombia will produce this year 11.5 million bags, a little
more than what was estimated before, 10.5 million bags, because of
better weather conditions, after a long raining season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
