<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Starts to Replace Canal's World War II Rails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The breaking of the concrete structures that support the steel
rails started with great speed in the Gatun sluices, in the
Atlantic, in order to reduce the time of waiting for the ships
that traverse the 80-kilometer long waterway.
</P>
<P>
Canal engineer Jose Reyes, in charge of the works, said that
the rails had to be replaced because of the increase in the
tonnage of the ships and the natural wear of the steel with time.
The canal was inaugurated in 1914.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said that the work is complicated because of the
structures that must be demolished, built to resist an eventual
air bombing by Japan against the Canal during World War II (1939-
1945).
</P>
<P>
The works include the remotion and replacing of several
kilometers of rail lines, the weight of which has not been
determined by the technicians.
</P>
<P>
The Panama Canal Authority (ACP) is also modernizing the
structure and widening the so-called "Culebra Cut" at a total cost
of one billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ACP said that the cut, 13 kilometer long and 15 meter deep,
has needed tons of explosives and the dredging of the Canal bottom,
with millions of cubic meters of mud and rocks, with the goal of
widening it from 152 meters to a minimum of 192 meters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
