<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Groups Resolved to Crack Down on Conflict Diamonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTWERP, Belgium, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The world's two largest
diamond trade groups Wednesday worked out a resolution on how to
crack down on conflict diamonds that have been used to fund wars
in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The resolution by the International Diamond Manufacturers
Association and the World Federation of Diamond Bourses came out
at the end of a three-day World Diamond Conference, held at the
world's largest diamond trading center.
</P>
<P>
"Over the three days of deliberations it was clear that the
feeling of everyone was that conflict diamonds are not acceptable,
" said Sean Cohen, president of the International Diamond
Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
The resolution called for an international system to certify as
legal rough diamonds bound for export and a global electronic
registry mechanism to monitor the export and import of rough
diamonds.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also wanted legislation by all countries
importing rough diamonds that would accept only diamond parcels
officially sealed and registered in the exporting countries.
</P>
<P>
It also warned to ban any dealer trading conflict diamonds that
are banned by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Both the diamond industry and opinion groups welcomed the
resolution that was a revised combination of two separate
resolutions by the two diamond groups.
</P>
<P>
The diamond industry is better known for its tradition of
secrecy by conducting million-dollar deals on a handshake.
</P>
<P>
The measures proposed by the Antwerp resolution are expected to
bring both transparency and control to trade of rough diamonds,
according to delegates to the conference.
</P>
<P>
Lax controls at international markets have been blamed for
allowing conflict diamonds to continue to reach the markets though
major diamond centers like Antwerp, Bombay of India, Tel Aviv of
Israel and New York have worked out tougher rules on certifying
the origins of diamonds.
</P>
<P>
The South African diamond conglomerate, De Beers, said that it
was instructing its 125 major diamond buyers not to purchase gems
from African conflict zones. The conglomerate controls 60 percent
of the uncut diamond market of the world.
</P>
<P>
The global diamond business obtains each year 6.8 billion U.S.
dollars from trade in rough diamonds which in turn generate a
retail diamond jewelry sales of around 56 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Antwerp is the world's largest diamond trading center, handling
some 80 percent of the world trade in rough diamonds and around 50
percent of the trade in polished gems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
