<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Feels "Pressure, Impatience" Over EU GMO Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- There was "pressure and
impatience" in the United States over the European Union's
moratorium on imports of genetically modified food and also
exasperation among U.S. corn farmers and exporters as well as the
lawmakers who represent them, a U.S. official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Robert LaRussa, acting U.S. undersecretary of commerce, said
despite the anger about the EU's stance on genetically modified
organisms (GMOs), the United States is not currently involved in
talks about filing a complaint on the issue to the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
But he said the GMOs was among the issues he discussed in talks
with European Commission officials this week.
</P>
<P>
The 15-country EU has had moratorium on new GMO approvals since
October 1998, while new legislation is being drafted. EU
environmental ministers agreed this month to keep the ban, but
European environment Commissioner Margot Wallstrom said she was
hopeful the ban would be lifted by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
However, some EU countries, such as France, are reluctant to
lift the ban until legislation is drawn up establishing the
liability of producers for any damage GMOs may cause to the
environment.
</P>
<P>
"Given consumer concerns in the United States, the United
States is not insensitive to the concerns of the European Union
and its consumers in this area," he told reporters here in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, however, it is a market access issue
ultimately to us. There is a lot of money in U.S. exports at stake,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
The undersecretary also welcomed the agreement reached at an EU-
U.S. summit in Lisbon in May to set up an independent panel to
review biotechnology issues, including genetically modified food.
</P>
<P>
Before the de facto ban imposed in October 1998, the EU
approved only 18 genetically modified products for sale or
production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
