<HEADLINE> Egypt to Build More First-aid Stations Along Highways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has decided to build more
first-aid stations along its highways to give emergency medical
care to people who are injured in traffic accidents, a medical
official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The government made this decision in a bid to rescue more people
injured in car crash because road accidents are frequent across
Egypt, Hashem Allam, director of the Emergency Medical Care
Department of the Health Ministry, was quoted as saying by the
country's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
A total of 387 stations will be set up every 30 to 50 kilometers
along the highways, Allam said, adding that they will be equipped
with ambulances and skilled medical workers, who will stand by
round the clock.
</P>
<P>
He did not mention the number of the existing stations and when
the new stations will be constructed.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry has worked out comprehensive and integrated
measures for saving the lives of citizens on highways, he said,
without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents are common in Egypt as vehicles are often
driven at high speed and rules are neglected. On Monday and
Tuesday, two serious accidents left a total of 31 people dead and
40 others injured when overcrowded mini-buses crashed head-on into
other vehicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
