<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriots Ready to Negotiate Cyprus Issue Seriously: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
said Wednesday that the Greek Cypriot side would be attending talks
on the Cyprus issue and is ready to negotiate seriously, "with
courage and flexibility," depending on the stand of the Turkish
Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
In a message issued on the occasion of the 26th anniversary of
the 1974 coup in which Turkey invaded and seized the northern third
of the Cyprus island, Clerides expressed hope that the
international community would succeed this time in persuading
Ankara to display the political will required to resolve the Cyprus
issue.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot and Turkish
Cypriot communities since the failed 1974 coup launched by
supporters for union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of United Nations-sponsored indirect talks on Cyprus
issue have been held since December 1999, aimed at preparing the
ground for substantive negotiations leading to a comprehensive
settlement.
</P>
<P>
The third round of talks started on July 5 in Geneva, but
adjourned in July 12. It will resume on July 24.
</P>
<P>
Clerides stressed that it is Greek Cypriots' "fervent desire" to
see a comprehensive settlement to the Cyprus issue achieved as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Greek Cypriots and Turkish Cypriots must find a
good solution which will heal the wounds of the past, overcome the
suspicion and sense of insecurity felt by both communities, dispel
their fears and concerns and consolidate a climate of confidence,
mutual understanding and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We must create, all together, new prospects for peace,
stability and security on the basis of the U.N. resolutions and
international law and legality so as to be able to enjoy the
benefits of harmonious coexistence and cooperation within the
European Union," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clerides reaffirmed that until a solution is found, the Cyprus
government will continue its policy of strengthening the defense
within the framework of the joint defense pact between Cyprus and
Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greece and the Greek Cypriot-dominated Cypriot government signed
a joint defense pact in November 1993, under which Greece will
provide Cyprus with air, sea and land cover in case of a fresh
Turkish offensive against Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
