<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The strike of a lightning Wednesday
halved the power generation capacity of unit No. 1 at the
Leningrad nuclear power plant outside St. Petersburg, the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
One transformer switched off automatically after the lightning
damaged insulators of a 320-kilowatt transmission line tower,
Interfax said, quoting Valery Arkhangelsky, the plant's operator.
</P>
<P>
The capacity of the unit, which normally stands at 1,000
megawatts, has fallen to 500.
</P>
