<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multichannel Companies to Dominate U.S. B2C Web Sales, Says Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 19 (Xinhua) -- A new study released Wednesday
said that multichannel retailers will dominate business-to-
consumer (B2C) sales over the Internet in the United States in a
few years.
</P>
<P>
U.S. B2C sales over the Web will grow from an estimated 25
billion U.S. dollars in 1999 to 152 billion dollars in 2002 and
233 billion dollars in 2004, according to the study by Giga
Information Group, a U.S. e-business advisor.
</P>
<P>
As a share of total U.S. consumer spending, Giga estimates
Internet sales will grow from 0.4 percent in 1999 to 3 percent in
2004. By 2002, multichannel retailers will dominate B2C sales
after sharing the growth with dot-com merchants and mail-order
converts.
</P>
<P>
"Consumer use of the Internet for product research will grow,
but the majority of sales will still close in stores where
consumers can touch products and take them home immediately," Giga
said in a report. "This pattern plays to the advantage of click-
and-mortar companies that can operate in real-world, and Internet
sales channels."
</P>
<P>
According to Giga's research, more than half of 1999's U.S. B2C
sales were handled by dot-com merchants. Although many analysts
and investors remain wary of the ability of some dot-coms to
survive their excessive burn rates, Giga foresees room on the
permanent retail landscape for dot-coms, predicting them to
capture 39 billion dollars in revenues in 2002 and 49 billion
dollars in 2004.
</P>
<P>
But the real B2C opportunity lies with multichannel retailing,
according to Giga. Companies with a real-world presence that build
Internet sales channels constituted 33 percent of B2C sales in
1999. Travel companies, brokerages and computer companies
dominated click-and-mortar sales. However, other click-and-mortar
companies like many chain stores showed evidence of real-world
retailers starting to compete effectively in this channel.
</P>
<P>
Giga expects these multichannel companies will dominate B2C
Internet sales by 2002, growing their share of Internet spending
to two-thirds of the market by 2002 from one-third in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
