<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Bilateral trade between Egypt and Germany reached 3.84
billion Deutsch marks (1.82 billion U.S. dollars), ranking Germany
Egypt's second largest trading partner.
</P>
<P>
A recent release by Bonn-based Egyptian Trade Representation
Bureau said Germany was the second biggest importer of Egyptian
goods, excluding oil, worth 394.6 million marks (187 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Egypt's main imports from Germany were electronic products,
mechanic equipment, medium goods while Egypt provided Germany with
farm products, textiles, iron and steel, and aluminium bars.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- In the first five months of this year, Egypt's Suez
Canal experienced a 5.6-million-ton increase in freight of oil
tankers as compared to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Over the period, 5,681 ships with total freight of 8.167 million
tons sailed through the Suez Canal, of which 990 ships were oil
tankers transporting net oil cargo of 34.736 million tons against
29.136 million tons in the corresponding period in l999.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Minister of Petroleum and Mineral Resources Ali
Bin Ibrahim al-N'aimi said the Arab American Company (ARAMCO)
located a new oil field in the kingdom's eastern region.
</P>
<P>
He said that ARAMCO on July 17 tested Al-Ghazal-1 well which was
drilled for the first time on April 28 this year, verifying
abundant reserve 4,084-4,163 meters deep while no hydrogen sulphide
was proven.
</P>
<P>
Tests on flow rate forecast a daily gas output of 17 million
cubic meters, he added.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's leading poultry farm Bandirma Vitaminli Yem
Sanayi A.S. (BANVIT) and International Finance Corporation (IFC)
signed a partnership and licence agreement.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, IFC will raise a total of 78 million
dollars to finance a BANVIT project covering a slaughterhouse, a
fodder factory, a data processing center and new incubation
facilities.
</P>
<P>
IFC will accordingly become the licensor company for the
BANVIT's new investments and hold its shares for the one-third of
the investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
