<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Returns Home After Syria Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
returned home Wednesday afternoon after a brief visit to Syria for
cementing ties, according to Jordan's official news agency Petra.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, who arrived in Syrian capital Damascus early in the
day, held talks with the newly-inaugurated Syrian President Bashar
al-Assad. They later presided over a meeting attended by senior
officials from both sides, said the report.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two sides discussed ways to promote
bilateral cooperation and the two leaders pledged to continue
coordination and consultation and intensify top-level meetings.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to hold the Joint Jordan-Syria Higher Committee
session soon to look into all bilateral issues such as trade
exchange, water, transport, and joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed regional situation and the latest
developments of the Middle East peace process, stressing their
support for all efforts towards a just and durable peace in the
region.
</P>
<P>
In this respect, King Abdullah reiterated Jordan's support for
Syria's demand for the return of the Golan Heights, seized by
Israel in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders stressed the need to revitalize the inter-Arab
unity for the interests and prospects of the Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian-Syrian ties cooled down after Amman signed a peace
treaty with Israel in l994. However, their bilateral relationship
gradually improved since Abdullah came to the throne in February
last year.
</P>
<P>
The two countries established a joint Free Trade and Industrial
Zone early this year. Syria has set free three Jordanian political
prisoners after they completed their jail terms as a goodwill
gesture.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said in Amman earlier this month that there were
brotherly and good-neighborly ties linking Jordan and Syria,
stressing that he noticed Bashar's keenness to develop ties with
Jordan and other Arab countries during their several previous
meetings.
</P>
<P>
Bashar was sworn in as Syrian president on July 17 after winning
overwhelming support in a sole-candidate national referendum,
succeeding his father, late President Hafez al-Assad, who died on
June 10 at age 69 after ruling Syria for three decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
