<HEADLINE> Ugandan PM Appreciates Sustained Cooperation With Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Ugandan Prime Minister Apolo
Nsibambi on Wednesday expressed appreciation for the sustained
cooperation between his country and Egypt in tourism, trade, water
resources and the pharmaceutical field.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding will be signed at the end of his
visit to stress the importance of continued cooperation between the
two countries in various areas, Nsibambi told reporters after
visiting Al-Salam Canal which channels Nile water to irrigate land
in Sinai.
</P>
<P>
He voiced hope that Egypt would help Uganda set up water
projects in order to face up to the problem of water shortage and
put an end to desertification, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Water Resources and Irrigation Mahmoud Abu
Zeid, who was accompanying Nsibambi, said that future opportunities
will be afforded for cooperation between Egypt and Uganda in
tourism, trade, water and other areas.
</P>
<P>
Abu Zeid added that the Ugandan delegation has met with a number
of Egyptian investors to discuss the possibility for them to
implement projects in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Nsibambi arrived in Cairo on Sunday for a five-day visit aimed
at expanding cooperation in various fields, especially in
developing water resources.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has provided Uganda with 13.5 million U.S. dollars in
grants for weeding its tropical lakes. It also sent Uganda
equipment and experts early last month to start the operation,
within the framework of common development among the Nile basin
countries. 
