<HEADLINE> Eastern Canada Sign Cooperative Pacts with New England, U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Several cooperative pacts were
signed Tuesday on education, disaster relief and environment in
Halifax, Nova Scotia, at the end of the 25th conference of the New
England governors and Eastern Canadian premiers.
</P>
<P>
Nova Scotia John Hamm, co-chairman of the two-day annual
meeting,hailed the deal on emergencies and disaster relief, saying
the agreement will commit the eatern region to providing aid in
case of a disaster such as the 1998 ice storm hitting Ontario and
Quebec.
</P>
<P>
Governor Angus King of Maine in New England spoke highly of the
cooperation between the two sides, declaring mercury emissions in
the region have been reduced by 40 percent since an action plan
was jointly developed two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The eastern leaders of the two countries also agreed to cut
mercury emissions by a further 20 percent by the year 2005, and by
50 percent by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement on education, the leaders decided to allow
students from both countries to transfer more easily into
different universities. 
</P>
