<HEADLINE> Remains of Pre-historic Elephant Unearthed in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Greek scientists recently found the
remains of a huge ancestor to the modern-day elephant in a field
in the northern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
The better-preserved of the two finds was probably a male,
standing some 4.5 meters tall and weighing more than 12 tonnes,
the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) quoted the scientists
as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A team of palaeontologists from Thessaloniki's Aristotelian
University reunited the recently uncovered cranium and a massive
jaw of a mastodon identified as the "Mammut Borsoni" with the
remains of two pre-historic pachyderms discovered three years ago
at the Milia region of northern Greece's Grevena prefecture.
</P>
</TEXT>
