<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The White House on Wednesday
said the negotiations at Camp David continued, denying earlier
reports that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak was planning to
quit the three-way Middle East peace summit.
</P>
<P>
"The White House has not been informed of anyone planning to
leave," spokesman Joe Lochkart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We checked with the spokesman for Prime Minister Barak, who
assured us there was neither a written nor an oral official
statement issued from Jerusalem this morning," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
He said that President Bill Clinton, who delayed his departure
for a summit of industrialized nations in Japan by one day, opened
the ninth day of talks at Camp David by meeting with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to leave sometime Thursday for Japan, with
or without a deal between the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
