<HEADLINE> U.S. Offers Africa 1 Billion Dollars a Year to Fight AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The United States will offer
one billion U.S. dollars a year in loans to sub-Saharan African
countries to help them buy U.S.-made drugs to fight AIDS, the U.S.
Export-Import Bank announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased to announce today a pilot program to finance
one billion dollars per year in exports of the most modern and
successful HIV- and AIDS-related pharmaceuticals and supplies to
sub-Saharan Africa -- at the lowest prices and on the friendliest
terms possible under the authority of this bank," James Harmon,
chairman of U.S. Export-Import Bank, said.
</P>
<P>
The move comes after five major U.S. drug companies agreed in
May to cut the prices they charge African nations for drugs to
combat AIDS and HIV virus.
</P>
<P>
But anti-AIDS drugs are costly even at discounted prices.
</P>
<P>
At a conference held in South Africa this month, U.N. officials
said an estimated three billion dollars are needed each year for
awareness drive, prevention and treatment of AIDS in African
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
