<HEADLINE> Explosive Device Causes Chaos in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- British police confirmed on
Wednesday that a suspect device exploded by a railway track in
west London was bomb.
</P>
<P>
Police conducted a controlled explosion on the device in the
suburb of Ealing near a main railway line into the city center as
thousands faced travel chaos.
</P>
<P>
The bomb alert triggered a series of security scares that
brought transport chaos to the capital hours before celebrations
in central London of the Queen Mother's 100th birthday.
</P>
<P>
The controlled explosion followed tip-offs from the Irish
capital Dublin early on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary Peter Mandelson blamed the
attack on renegade Irish Republican guerrillas opposed to Northern
Ireland's peace process.
</P>
<P>
Dissident Irish republican guerrillas were blamed by security
sources when a bomb damaged a bridge over the River Thames in west
London in June, causing no casualties.
</P>
<P>
Police were investigating further security alerts at the
central London underground rail stations of Victoria and
Westminster, near the houses of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Both stations were evacuated and cordoned off.
</P>
<P>
London Underground said it had suspended services on parts of
several lines in central London at the request of police.
</P>
<P>
The overground rail service to London's Heathrow airport was
completely suspended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
