<HEADLINE> Annan Hopes There Would be Some Sort of Progress From Mideast Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 19 (Xinhua -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Wednesday expressed the hope that there would be some
sort of progress from the ongoing Mideast summit.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who just returned from his trip to Europe and Africa,
told the press that the Mideast summit was at a very critical
stage as U.S. President Bill Clinton would be leaving for Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
"What I will say is to urge all parties to really focus on the
issues in the spirit of give and take and make the kind of
compromise that is necessary for them to get compromises so that
we can move on," the Secretary-General said.
</P>
<P>
"I hope there will be some sort of progress before he leaves,"
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"I have been in touch with a senior member of the Palestinian
team. But I can't tell you what we discussed because of the
blackout," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the summit began on July 11 at David Camp, U.S.
President Clinton has been shuttling between Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, trying
to shepherd them toward an accord on the most painful and divisive
issues: the boundaries of a future Palestinian state, the fate of
several million Palestinian refugees and the status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton has delayed his departure for Japan by a day
to give negotiators a last chance to break their deadlock.
</P>
