<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Federal Court Rejects Marcos Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland's Federal Court has
turned down an appeal by the family of former Philippines ruler
Ferdinand Marcos to block the repatriation of disputed money in
Swiss accounts,according to a Swiss Radio International report
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The court ruled that the Marcos family cannot invoke the
statute of limitations to prevent disputed assets in Switzerland
from being sent back to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The ruling came in response to an appeal by the brother-in-law
of the secretary of Marcos's wife, Imelda. He was seeking to
prevent the Zurich legal authorities from sending information to
the Philippines on an account he holds through a Panama-registered
company.
</P>
<P>
The account, which contains about 10 million Swiss francs (
about 6.6 million U.S. dollars), has been frozen since 1986, when
Marcos fled the Philippines to avoid being overthrown.
</P>
<P>
The court said that since Switzerland was merely offering
Manila legal assistance in the case, Philippine law and not Swiss
law was applicable. It noted that in a recent ruling, the
Philippine Supreme Court said the state's right to claim the
restitution of assets illegally acquired by state officials was
not subject to a statute of limitations.
</P>
<P>
A total of 620 million francs (about 370 million U.S. dollars)
has so far been transferred to the Philippines, where it remains
blocked until the legal process against the Marcos family and its
allies has been concluded. There are another 35 million francs (
about 21 million dollars) being frozen in Swiss accounts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Religious Parties Asks Govt to Ban Cable Networks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Religious parties in Pakistan's
Northwest Frontier Province (NWFP) Wednesday urged the government
to immediately ban cable networks in the province, otherwise they
will take actions against the cable owners.
</P>
<P>
Around 23 Islamic groups formed an alliance against the
government move to legalize cable networks in the country and set
July 23 for the ban on the cables.
</P>
<P>
"Cable network is un-Islamic and the religious groups will take
actions if the government fails to remove all cables," Maulana
Abdul Malik, secretary general of the alliance namely "Islamic
Revolutionary Council" told a news conference in NWFP capital
Peshawar.
</P>
<P>
A verdict by the Peshawar High Court, which permitted cable
networks in the province last month, has prompted the religious
parties' strong reaction to the cable business.
</P>
<P>
NWFP Governor Mohammad Shafiq banned cable networks in the
province two months ago. Cable owners in the province challenged
the ban in the Peshawar High Court, which declared the ban as
illegal.
</P>
<P>
Maulana Malik asked the military government to dismiss the
judge who permitted the "un-Islamic" cables. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
