<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Hits New Record in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit rose 1.8
percent in May to a record level of 31 billion U.S. dollars as
America's trade imbalance with oil-producing nations climbed to
its second-highest point ever, the Commerce Department reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Total imports of goods and services fell 0.3 percent in May to
116.8 billion dollars from 117.1 billion dollars in April. But
exports fell more sharply by 1 percent to 85.7 billion dollars,
thus widening May's trade gap.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. deficit with oil-producing nations jumped by 17.8
percent in May to 4.1 billion dollars, second-highest on record.
Imports from the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
rose to 5.4 billion dollars in May, also the second-highest ever.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of this year, the trade deficit was
147.7 billion dollars, compared with 92.6 billion dollars during
the same period last year. For all of last year, the deficit
soared to a record 265 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the strength of the U.S. dollar against other key
currencies, which tends to make U.S. goods more expensive abroad,
was a key reason for the continued record level of the U.S. trade
deficit.
</P>
<P>
As expected, trade gaps with major U.S. trading partners
increased in May, as American consumers continued to draw in
imports even after a string of interest-rate hikes.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit with Japan narrowed by 5.4 percent in May to
6.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The deficit with the United States' North American Free Trade
Agreement partners Canada and Mexico rose to a record 6.41 billion
dollars in May.
</P>
<P>
Broken down, the gap with Canada increased to 3.96 billion
dollars from 3.70 billion dollars in April, while the deficit with
Mexico rose more sharply to 2.45 billion dollars in May from 1.45
billion dollars in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The deficit with Western Europe rose to 5.69 billion dollars in
May from 4.65 billion dollars in April. But the trade deficit with
Japan eased in May to 6.94 billion dollars from 7.33 billion
dollars in the previous month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
