<HEADLINE> Khatami Urged by Lawmakers to Reshuffle Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- More than 210 out of a total of 290
Iranian lawmakers on Wednesday urged President Mohammad Khatami to
take immediate action to reshuffle his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
In their letter to the president, the lawmakers called on
Khatami's government to submit a bill to the parliament within a
month on the merger of several ministries doing similar jobs, the
official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Since restructuring the government organization and merger of
several ministries are on your agenda, the parliament is expected
to receive the relevant bill to debate the matter," the letter was
read at an open session of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers believed the plan to merge at least three
ministries is necessary to improve government administration and is
the best way to solve the problems of the ministries working in the
field of energy and those working in the fields of agriculture,
livestock breeding, rural development, industries, mines and
metals, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
Since the reformists' landslide victory in the February
parliamentary elections, Khatami has been urged to make big changes
in his cabinet, a coalition of reformists, centrists and leftists.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the reformist circle had predicted that Khatami would
change at least eight ministers and several vice presidents once
the new parliament dominated by reformists was formed on May 27.
The aim was to remove those who were not fully coordinated with the
reformists.
</P>
<P>
Khatami's current cabinet, formed in August 1997, consists of
reformists of the Islamic Iran Participation Front (IIPF),
centrists of the Party of Constructive Executives of Iran (PCEI)
and leftists of the Assembly of Combatant Clergy (ACC).
</P>
<P>
However, relations between reformists and centrists soured
before the February elections as the IIPF strongly opposed the
participation of former President Hashemi Rafsanjani in the race
while the PCEI supported him to run for a seat in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Khatami last month appointed former Minister of Post, Telegraph
and Telephones Mohammad Reza Aref to head the newly formed State
Management and Planning Organization, a merger of the Planning and
Budget Organization and the Civil Administration and Recruitment
Organization.
</P>
<P>
This signalled the beginning of the scheduled reshuffle, which
was expected to also involve the first vice president, vice
president for executive affairs, ministers of defense, culture and
Islamic guidance, interior, education as well as economic and
financial affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
