<HEADLINE> Legislation Proposed to Curb Money Laundering in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's Central Bank Governor Riad
Salameh is proposing a legislation that would modify the country's
laws against money laundering to be in line with the world campaign
against dirty money, a local newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Salameh said in a statement that the proposed legislation will
not entail relaxation of the banking secrecy law, long considered
the cornerstone of Lebanon's successful banking sector.
</P>
<P>
"We have to respond to the request of the international group
charged with fighting money laundering by modifying our laws and
devising a mechanism for removing banking secrecy in case any
suspect money is detected," Salameh told Al Mustaqbal newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he ruled out the possibility of a complete lifting of
banking secrecy due to the national consensus on maintaining it.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has been accused of not cooperating with international
efforts to combat money laundering not because any money laundering
takes place in Lebanon, "but because of its laws" which need to be
upgraded without necessarily affecting the banking secrecy law.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank governor's remarks coincided with another
interview carried by An Nahar newspaper with Partick Mollet,
secretary general of the international group for combating money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
Mollet reportedly said that there was no intention to harm
Lebanon or undermine its banking secrecy law which he deemed "
legitimate." "All we are asking is to modify Lebanon's laws so that
they don't appear to conflict with the efforts to fight money
laundering," he added.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the Lebanese law should be made flexible
enough to enable specialized international authorities to probe and
investigate suspect funds that move across borders. Other countries
confiscate dirty money, but Lebanon usually turns such money back
to where it came from. 
</P>
</TEXT>
