<HEADLINE> Turkey Concerned With Iran's Missile Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Huseyin Dirioz, deputy spokesman of
Turkish Foreign Ministry, said on Wednesday that Ankara was
concerned about Iran's test of the Shahab-3 medium-range missile
four days ago.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's daily Milliyet reported that Iran successfully tested
its Shahab-3 missile with a range of 1,300 kilometers on July 15
and Turkish intelligence organization claimed that most of the
missiles with warheads carrying chemical weapons have targeted
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Dirioz said at a news briefing that because of its geography,
Turkey has been "sensitive" on the risk of proliferation of weapons
of mass destruction in its neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey is sensitive about Iran's second test of the Shahab-3
medium-range missile on July 15. We are closely monitoring the
developments," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Mohammad Hussein Lavasani, Iranian ambassador
to Turkey, said that Iran's Shahab-3 medium-range ballistic
missiles did not pose a threat against Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"The missiles were not against a third country," said Lavasani
following his one-hour meeting with Ugur Ziyal, deputy
undersecretary of Turkish Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said that the issue of the missiles was not taken up at the
meeting, rejecting claims that the Shahab-3 missiles will pose
threats to neighboring countries, including Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Tehran and Ankara soured on several fronts. On
top of the long-standing accusations made by Turkey is Iran's
permission to Kurdish separatists who have since 1984 fighting for
an independent Kurdish state in southeast Turkey to operate from
bases inside Iran.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit accused Tehran on May 17 of
wanting "to export" its Islamic revolution to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Turkish press launched a huge campaign
accusing Iran of being behind a series of assassinations of non-
religious Turkish intellectuals in the 1980s and 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Tehran has vehemently denied the accusations while lodging
official protests at what it terms "huge" arrests of Iranians in
Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
Iran is also highly critical of Ankara's military cooperation
with Israel, which Iran refused to recognize. Turkey has also sent
Iran a detailed dossier drawn up by its security forces on the
Turkish Hizbollah, a secretive fundamentalist organization
suspected of carrying out hundreds of assassinations in Turkey with
support from Iran.
</P>
<P>
Amid the tension, Turkish President Ahmet Necdet Sezer decided
not to attend a summit of the regional Economic Cooperation
Organization (ECO) held in Tehran early last month.
</P>
<P>
Iran, Turkey and Pakistan were founder members of the
organization back in 1985, with the aim of establishing a "Muslim
common market" with cooperation and regional discussion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
