<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Announces Policy on Internet Banking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 19 (Xinhua)-- The Monetary Authority of
Singapore (MAS) Wednesday announced that internet banking will
operate within the same prudential framework as traditional
banking but banks should be responsible for assessing and managing
the risks associated with their operations in internet banking.
</P>
<P>
In a policy statement on its approach to the licensing,
regulation and supervision of internet banking in Singapore, MAS
said that internet banking, including internet-only banks (IOBs)
will operate within the same prudential framework as traditional
banking and MAS' admission criteria for new license applicants and
its regulatory and supervisory approach will apply across the
board.
</P>
<P>
The MAS announced that MAS' existing policy already allows all
banks licensed in Singapore to use the internet to provide their
services and MAS is prepared to grant new banking licenses to
Singapore-incorporated banking groups wishing to set up banking
subsidiaries to pursue new business models.
</P>
<P>
This will give a Singapore-incorporated bank the flexibility to
decide whether to engage in internet banking by way of a
subsidiary or by using a division within the bank, the MAS added.
</P>
<P>
Should a Singapore-incorporated bank choose to set up a
subsidiary in alliance with joint-venture partners, the MAS said,
the bank will be required as a must to maintain more than 50
percent of shareholding in the subsidiary bank and the chairman of
the subsidiary bank must be appointed by the Singapore-
incorporated parent.
</P>
<P>
The MAS also has decided to impose a minimum paid-up capital
requirement of 100 million Singapore dollars (about 58 million U.S.
dollars) on banking subsidiaries whose Singapore-incorporated
parent banks have already met 1.5 billion Singapore dollars (about
0.87 billion U.S. dollars) and all banking subsidiaries will
continue to be subject to MAS' current Capital Adequacy Ratio
requirement of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
The lower minimum paid-up capital requirement will apply to all
Singapore-incorporated bank subsidiaries, MAS added.
</P>
<P>
MAS stated that its current framework for prudential regulation
and supervision provides flexibility for innovation in new
business models and technologies and there is no need for a new
prudential framework to manage or mitigate the risks involved in
internet banking.
</P>
<P>
However, the MASA emphasized that bank management must pay
special attention to the security, technology-related, liquidity
and operational risks which may be accentuated in internet banking.
</P>
<P>
Given the different models of internet banking that will be in
play, the MAS said, a risk-focused supervisory approach to
individual banks is more suitable than "one-size-fits-all"
regulation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Diamond Industry to Clamp Down on Conflict Diamond Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTWERP, Belgium, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The world diamond
industry on Wednesday announced their intent and measures to
combat trading in conflict diamonds that have been used to fund
wars in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Some 350 diamond miners, dealers, cutters, polishers and
government representatives from around the world decided after
three days of conference to introduce new strict measures to close
off all legal loopholes through which conflict diamonds have been
entering the international market.
</P>
<P>
One of the new measures will be a certification system to
monitor rough diamonds from the mines where they are found all the
way to international trading centers.
</P>
<P>
Any dealers found trading on conflict diamonds will face tough
penalty as losing qualification as diamond dealers.
</P>
<P>
The three-day World Diamond Conference, that ended on Wednesday,
formed an International Diamond Council from the existing
International Diamond Manufacturers Association and the World
Federation of Diamond Bourses.
</P>
<P>
The newly-formed council will serve as a supervising body over
the international cooperation in the fight against conflict
diamonds.
</P>
<P>
An international outcry over the use of revenues from trade on
illegal diamonds to fund wars in Africa where lots of people have
been killed snatched the limelight at this year's conference, held
at the world's largest diamond trading center.
</P>
<P>
The biannual event happened to follow a United Nations embargo
over Sierra Leone diamonds in an attempt to cut off funding for
the African country's Revolutionary United Front.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. embargo on the export of Sierra Leone diamonds has
raised a call for global measures to stop the smuggling of
diamonds from one African country to another in order to
circumvent national laws and international sanctions.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. report published in March on sanctions against illegal
Angolan diamonds used to fund the UNITA criticized some companies
in the diamond industry for allegedly allowing trade on what has
been described as conflict diamonds to flourish.
</P>
<P>
But observers believed that it would not be easy in that the
complicated chain system of dealers will only make diamond trade
difficult to track and therefore difficult to halt trade of
conflict diamonds.
</P>
<P>
Apart from diamond-producing countries in Africa, Russia and
Canada were also present while such diamond-cutting centers as
India, Belgium, Thailand, Israel and the United States also
attended the conference.
</P>
<P>
The global diamond business each year produces 6.8 billion U.S.
dollars from trade on rough diamonds which in turn generate a
retail diamond jewelry sales of around 56 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Threatens to Quit Talks: Israeli Source </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak is preparing to walk out of the Middle East peace summit in
Camp David without a deal with the Palestinians, a senior Israeli
source said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Barak is preparing to return home at the soonest moment after
it became clear to him that the Palestinians are not a true
partner for peace," the source was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said Israel was warning the Palestinians "not to take
unilateral steps or inflame violence in the region."
</P>
<P>
But Barak's official spokesman Gadi Baltiansky refused to
comment on the report. "I cannot comment on this report," he said.
</P>
<P>
Angered by a U.S. proposal reportedly adopting Israeli
positions, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat also threatened to
leave Camp David on July 13 but was later pacified by President
Bill Clinton who promised to present a new version of proposal.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, Barak and Arafat have met in the Camp David
presidential retreat in Maryland since July 11 in a bid to work
out a framework agreement for a final settlement of the Israeli-
Palestinian conflict.
</P>
<P>
Clinton announced early Wednesday that he would delay by one
day his planned departure for Japan to attend a summit of the
industrialized nations to give a last chance for Barak and Arafat
to strike a deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
