<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Influential Tycoon Quits Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma Wednesday
passed a resolution accepting the resignation of Boris Berezovsky,
an influential business tycoon, from the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was passed by a vote of 346-5 with two
abstentions, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Berezovsky announced his intention to give up his seat in the
parliament on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Speaker Vladimir Zhirinovsky said that Berezovsky should
be thanked as this was "the first time in the history of the
Russian parliament that a deputy has courageously given up his
powers after understanding that he cannot fulfill his obligations.
"
</P>
<P>
Berezovsky said he decided to cede parliamentary immunity so as
to be in the same position as the other oligarchs, whom he said
were facing a state-run campaign against the business community.
</P>
<P>
He was apparently referring to a series of high-profile probes
into alleged embezzlement and fraud by businessmen such as media
magnet Vladimir Gusinsky, whose property was announced seized on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was "no accident, not the initiative of some over-
zealous bureaucrat; it is aimed at essentially destroying large
independent businesses," Interfax quoted Berezovsky as saying at a
press conference on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, Berezovsky said he planned to build a "
constructive opposition to the authorities."
</P>
<P>
"I have enough strength to curb the authorities," he told
reporters shortly after he officially announced his resignation as
a deputy at the State Duma session.
</P>
<P>
Berezovsky became a deputy after winning last December's
parliamentary elections in Karachayevo-Cherkessia, a tiny region
in southwestern Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
