<HEADLINE> Russia Sees Higher Grain Harvest in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Russia will produce at least 65
million tons of grain this year, higher than a harvest of 54.7
million tons last year, Deputy Prime Minister and Agriculture
Minister Aleksei Gordeyev said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"This year is going well for Russia's agricultural sector, and
a harvest of 65 million tons of grain will make it possible to
meet most of the country's food grain needs," the Interfax news
agency quoted Gordeyev as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, he said there "will be a small deficit of feed grain,
largely of those crops (maize and soybeans) that Russia has
historically never produced in sufficient quantities." 
</P>
</TEXT>
