<HEADLINE> Dekker Wins 17th Stage, Armstrong Helds on Overall Leads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
GENEVA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Dutchman Erik Dekker won the 17th
stage of the Tour de France on Wednesday but Lance Armstrong still
stayed on the overall lead.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Postal captain's position was never threatened
throughout the 155-kilometer race, as he remained within the pack
with his closest challengers. Jan Ullrich of Germany's Deutsche
Telekom remained in second place, still 5 minutes, 37 seconds
behind Armstrong, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
Dekker of Rabobank edged out Erik Zabel of Telekom and little-
known Fred Rodriguez, an American riding for the Italian Mapei
team, to take his third stage win of this year's Tour.
</P>
<P>
The riders went from the French southern shore of Lake Geneva
into the nearby foothills of the Alps before a frantic race
downhill to Lausanne, the Swiss home of the International Olympic
Committee on the lake's northern shore.
</P>
<P>
Also Wednesday, Armstrong and the race's eight other top
riders passed a surprise blood test taken in their hotel rooms. It
marked the latest step taken by International Cycling Union to
restore public confidence in the integrity of the competition
following a scandal-plagued Tour in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Massimiliano Lelli of Italy led the pack during Wednesday's
toughest challenge, a steep climb to the top of the 1,445-meter
Col de Mosses east of Lake Geneva. But a gaggle of pursuers
eventually swallowed up Lelli on the downhill side.
</P>
<P>
130 riders among the 180 who started the race July 1 remained
at Wednesday's finish. The lone American-sponspored team,U.S.
Postal, is the only one with all nine members still competing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
