<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Slams U.N. Oil-For-Food Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammad Mehdi
Salah on Wednesday slammed the United Nations oil-for-food program
for failing to meet the objective of easing the living conditions
of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's crude exports since 1996 under the oil-for-food program
have generated 29 billion U.S. dollars, while the value of goods
delivered to Iraq was only 7.5 billion dollars, Salah said.
</P>
<P>
Salah made the remarks when meeting the visiting Romanian
delegation which came to the Iraqi capital to attend the 32nd
anniversary of the Iraq's July revolution in 1968.
</P>
<P>
Salah said that since the oil-for-food was implemented in late
1996, the U.N. has granted 9 billion dollars of compensation to the
victims of the 1991 Gulf War, while Iraq only received 2 billion
dollars a year for its 22 million people.
</P>
<P>
This is in sharp comparison with the situation before the U.N.
sanctions were imposed on Iraq, when Iraq spent about 20 billion
dollars yearly to ensure the needs of the Iraqi people, Salah said.
</P>
<P>
The trade minister condemned the United States and British
delegates at the U.N. Sanctions Committee for blocking the
contracts Iraq signed with foreign countries to import food,
medicine and other humanitarian goods within the framework of the
oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly slammed the U.N. humanitarian deal for not
being able to meet Iraq's needs. The deal allows Iraq to export
crude every six months to finance imports of humanitarian goods to
help offset the crippling impacts of the U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed wide-ranging economic and trade sanctions on
Iraq after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait, which triggered the 1991
Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyers of Iranian Jews Reject Court Ruling in Espionage Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Defense lawyers of the Iranian Jews
convicted in an espionage case have raised protest against the
court ruling, spokesman of the lawyers Esmaeel Naseri Mojarad
announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mojarad said he has submitted a 95-page petition to the Islamic
Revolutionary Court of Shiraz, capital of southern Fars Province,
in protest against the ruling of the court on July 1, announcing
two to 13 years prison terms on 10 Jews and two Muslims, while
acquitting the other three Jews and two Muslims accused.
</P>
<P>
He said the lawyers of the Jews had cited legal and judicial
reasons to reject the court ruling, the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The verdict found the convicted guilty of being members of a
spying network formed by Eshaq Belanas, an Iranian Jew who was said
to have fled the country in 1991.
</P>
<P>
However, the verdict has acquitted the accused of spying charges
of collection and transfer of classified information, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that if the accused were convicted of membership in a
spying network, their sentences should be between 3 months and 5
years in prison according to article 499 of the Islamic penal code.
</P>
<P>
The Jews and the Muslims were arrested more than one year ago in
Shiraz. The arrest and trial of the Iranian Jews sparked protests
from Israel, which denied any links with the accused, and Western
countries, who demanded Iran of their release.
</P>
<P>
Iran insists that the case has nothing to do with religious
beliefs and no foreign country should interfere in its domestic
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Iran has a Jewish community of about 25,000 people, the largest
in the Middle East outside Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tehran Stock Exchange Index Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The general price index at Tehran
Stock Exchange on Wednesday closed at 2442.68 points, up 1.97
points from Tuesday's finish.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,182,318 shares changed hands in 937 deals and the
turnover was 3.25 billion rials (about 1.08 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The shares of 18 companies registered gains while those of 5
others declined. 
</P>
