<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Approves Final Draft on Upper House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Russia's lower house of parliament
on Wednesday approved the finalized version of a draft law on
reorganizing the country's upper chamber.
</P>
<P>
The document was the revised edition of a motion tabled by
President Vladimir Putin on forming the Federation Council
following weeks of work by a conciliation commission composed of
members from the government and both chambers.
</P>
<P>
It cleared the Duma by a vote of 308-88 with five abstentions,
well above the 226 votes needed for approval, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the document, heads of the regional governments and
legislatures will no longer hold the two seats for each of the
regions, as is the case now. Instead, the seats will be held by
two representatives, one from the regional legislature and the
other from the government.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the regional parliaments will be elected for
the term the parliament is working. In territories with bicameral
parliaments, two representatives will be elected alternately from
each house for half the term.
</P>
<P>
Candidates to the Federation Council are to be proposed by
parliament chairman. Alternative candidacies may be proposed by a
group of at least one-third of the deputies.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the regional governments are to be appointed
by heads of the local executive authorities -- the governor in the
regions and the president in the constituent republics.
</P>
<P>
In another legislative development Wednesday, the Duma overrode
the Federation Council's veto on amendments to the federal law on
the general principles of legislative and executive government
bodies.
</P>
<P>
The bill was approved in the initial reading with 362 votes in
favor, 35 against and eight abstentions. The required majority was
300 votes.
</P>
<P>
The amendments give the president the right to temporarily
remove and dismiss heads of territorial executive bodies for
breaking the law and on the grounds of court decisions.
</P>
<P>
In addition to a court ruling, the president's move requires a
note from the Prosecutor General confirming that criminal charges
have been brought against a governor.
</P>
<P>
The amendments also provide for the dissolution of territorial
parliaments if they violate federal law. To this end, the
president will have to submit a corresponding bill to the Duma.
</P>
<P>
The amendments initiated by President Vladimir Putin will now
be submitted for his approval, bypassing the Federation Council,
Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Travel Banned in Canada's Park Where Anthrax Kills 22 Bison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- A travel ban has been imposed in a
northwestern Canadian national park after 22 bison were recently
found dead in an outbreak of anthrax, a disease caused by a
bacillus that could also be transmitted to man.
</P>
<P>
Officials in the Northwest Territories region confirmed
Wednesday they are taking precautions against a possible spread of
the disease after bison carcasses were discovered in Wood Buffalo
National Park, which straddles the northern part of Alberta
province and the southern part of the Northwest Territories.
</P>
<P>
A bison ecologist is monitoring the situation while the ban is
put into place in the northern Alberta part of the national park,
which is about 180 kilometers southwest of Fort Smith in the
Northwest Territories.
</P>
<P>
Ray Case, spokesman for the territories department of resources,
stressed the travel ban as a precaution to ensure that people don'
t come into contact with the diseased carcasses.
</P>
<P>
"In the past when Wood Buffalo National Park has had an
outbreak, we haven't seen any transfer of it to other populations,
" said the spokesman, adding there has been no sign of the deadly
disease spreading so far.
</P>
<P>
No humans have been infected by anthrax in Alberta since 1948,
although a number of cattle died from the disease as lately as
last year in the western province, officials say.
</P>
<P>
They believe the cattle deaths were resulted from spores left
behind decades ago when bison roamed the southern half of the
province.
</P>
<P>
Anthrax is an infectious disease of wild or domesticated
animals, such as cattle and sheep, which is characterized by black
pustules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
