<HEADLINE> Russian Parliament Ratifies Friendship Treaty With DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma on Wednesday
overwhelmingly ratified the Treaty of Friendship, Neighborliness
and Cooperation with the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (
DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The treaty cleared the lower house of parliament by a vote of
363-8 with one abstention. The required majority was 266 votes.
</P>
<P>
The ratification coincided with the visit to DPRK by Russian
President Vladimir Putin, who arrived in Pyongyang earlier
Wednesday on the first trip by a Russian head of state to the
north Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Ivan Ivanov, who presented the
document before the lawmakers, said the treaty allows the two
countries "to jointly fight for peace and disarmament, which will
bring our partner out of international isolation to a significant
extent," the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The treaty opens up great opportunities for cooperation,
including with South Korea, and the possibility to influence the
unification processes on the Korean peninsula, Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
The new friendship treaty, which was reached after talks that
lasted for three years, replaces the 1961 treaty between the
Soviet Union and the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Chairman of the State Duma Committee for
International Affairs Dmitry Rogozin, Russian Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov said the old treaty "is obsolete and does not reflect
the new situation."
</P>
<P>
The parliament of the DPRK ratified the new treaty on April 6,
2000 "without any reservations," Ivanov said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
