<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM on Arms Robbery by Al-Ma'unah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Wednesday night he felt the incident of the
arms robbery from military camps in Gerik in the northern state of
Perak on July 2 began with efforts to discredit the government.
</P>
<P>
"Beginning with the accusation that the government is unIslamic,
they began to win support for certain groups through a campaign of
hatred claiming that the government is unIslamic," he said when
analyzing the incident in a "Special Interview with the prime
minister" aired over Radio and TV Malaysia (RTM) and TV3
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
In the July 2 incident which occurred for the first time in
Malaysia's history of independence, 15 men posing as army officers
stole a huge arms cache including more than 100 rifles, machine-
guns and thousands of rounds of ammunition from two military camps
in Gerik and they joined 13 accomplices hiding in the Bukit
Jenalik jungle in Sauk in the state where they took four hostages -
- a durian collector, a soldier and two police personnel.
</P>
<P>
One of the gang members was killed in a crossfire with security
forces and the remaining 27 surrendered to the authorities five
days later but after killing two of the hostages -- a soldier and
a police detective.
</P>
<P>
The gang members were all identified as belonging to the Al-Ma'
unah religious deviationist and mystical cult.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said his initial fears were that the arms robbery
could perhaps be the beginning of an armed rebellion in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"I was worried as to whether this was the beginning of
something bigger ... that there is to be a planned rebellion in
our country and probably result in many deaths, killings and so on.
I was greatly shocked as this does not normally happen in our
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, from the latest information and the results of
investigations the government has been able to identify who did it
and what was their real aim. "We are monitoring the situation as
this is what we fear most," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the opposition is trying to absolve the Al-Ma'
unah group of the criminal act of staging the arms heist and the
Sauk hostage episode by charging that it was the government's own
doing.
</P>
<P>
"We have now seen that to protect those directly or indirectly
involved or those sympathizing with the group, they hurl
accusations that the government planned the heist," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
The accusations did not make sense at all and moreover the
government would never at all get involved in criminal acts which
resulted in the murder of two members of the security forces,
Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
The wholly baseless accusations would no doubt create feelings
of anger among Muslims who hoped that this country would follow
methods which they could consider were in line with Islamic
governance, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
