<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S.Lankan President Faces Uphill Battle to Push Through Constitutional Reforms  by Lian Guohui </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga is facing a uphill battle to push through her long
cherished constitutional reforms in the face of divergence with
the main opposition United National Party (UNP), dissatisfaction
from moderate Tamil parties, and a total rejection by Tamil Tiger
rebels, political analysts said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ruling People's Alliance (PA) led by President Kumaratunga
struck consensus with the UNP on the proposed constitutional
reforms in early July after four months of arduous bipartisan
talks, but divergence remains in issues of the Executive
Presidency and the practical implementation of the reforms,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga wants to keep the Executive Presidency in a
transitional period extending to the end of her second six-year
presidential term in 2005, but the UNP wanted a shorter time frame.
</P>
<P>
"We will not agree to the continuation of the executive
presidency in any form, even for a transitional period. The UNP
Executive Committee has called for the abolition of the Executive
Presidency," said Mahinda Samarasinghe, a UNP member of parliament
(MP) and one of the representatives to the government-UNP
constitutional negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The constitutional reforms, first put forward by the president
in 1995 in the form of devolution package, aim to end Sri Lanka's
long-running ethnic conflict by devolving more powers to regions
including one administered by minority Tamils. The reforms will
turn the island into a de facto federal state with Westminster
style parliamentary system.
</P>
<P>
Moderate Tamil parties have also reacted vehemently towards the
proposed new constitution, deeming it "totally ignores the
political aspirations of the Tamil nation." Eight Tamil parties
said in a joint statement on Sunday that the proposed new
constitution did not guarantee the unity of the Tamil northeastern
region, which Tamils view as their homeland.
</P>
<P>
The parties demanded radical modification to the draft
constitution. They urged the PA government and UNP to put an end
to the war and initiated third-party mediation to bring the
government and the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels
to the negotiation table as the first step to bring peace to the
war-ridden country.
</P>
<P>
With the current parliament to be dissolved on August 24, and
new parliamentary election due on the first week of November,
President Kumaratunga needs Tamil MPs' support to achieve the two-
thirds majority in the parliament for the adoption of the new
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga faces an arduous task of retaining her ruling bloc'
s hold on the 225-member parliament, as she herself got onto the
presidency last December with a mere 51.2 percent public vote.
</P>
<P>
Her People's Alliance, together with two small parties, managed
a one-seat majority in 1994 parliamentary election, but enjoys
support of some opposition defectors as well as minority Tamil MPs.
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga has said she would present the draft
constitution before the parliament in early August and have it
adopted before the parliament is dissolved on August 24.
</P>
<P>
However, even if the new constitution gets passed in the
parliament, it is still good-for-nothing without the cooperation
of the LTTE rebels who have been fighting for a separate homeland
called Eelam for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's North and East
since 1983. Up until now, the reaction from the rebel organization
is total rejection.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE's spokesman and main theoretician Balasingham said his
organization had refused government's 1995 devolution package, how
could they accept such a draft constitution which grant even fewer
autonomous rights for ethnic Tamils now?
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga still faces opposition from Sinhala Urumaya (
Heritage), a newly founded Sinhala nationalist party who has vowed
to campaign against the draft constitution, saying it was
tantamount to separation.
</P>
<P>
Influential Buddhist clergies in this predominantly Buddhist
country also protested against the removal of an article in the
draft which grants the foremost place to Buddhism and ensures its
protection, accusing the government and UNP of doing so to pacify
the separatist LTTE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Navy Chief Warns Foreign Warships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Navy Chief of Staff Adm.
Achmad Sutjipto Wednesday said he did not believe foreign warships
would dare to trespass on Indonesian waters to intervene in the
Maluku conflict.
</P>
<P>
"It's not likely to happen. The risks would be too high. I
think no country would purposely provoke an incident at sea,"
Sutjipto told reporters in Surabaya, capital of East Java.
</P>
<P>
The Navy chief was commenting on reports that a United States
warship had recently been spotted sailing in the vicinity of Biak
in Irian Jaya province.
</P>
<P>
Sutjipto confirmed that the Navy had detected the U.S. warship'
s presence but said its position was still outside Indonesian
territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
"If they want to enter Indonesian territorial waters, they will
have to respect our rules as a sovereign country," he said, adding
that an intrusion into Indonesian territory would badly damage
diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
He said he had ordered all of the Navy's units in the provinces
of Maluku and North Maluku to carry out their duties without any
hesitation.
</P>
<P>
To date, the Navy had seized 139 civilian ships carrying
weapons illegally in Maluku waters and 21 ships in North Maluku.
</P>
<P>
It had questioned 1,300 people, both civilians and military,
about their involvement in weapon smuggling.
</P>
<P>
"We check all ships (sailing among the Maluku islands). If they
resist, we will take stern measures, including sinking them, if
necessary," he was quoted by the Antara News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Navy so far had not come across any foreign ship
transporting weapons illegally but was not ruling out the
possibility that warring elements in Maluku were receiving weapons
from overseas.
</P>
<P>
"Our territorial waters covering such a vast area, it is too
naive to think there can be no arms supply from abroad," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spice islands of Maluku have been wrecked by communal
clashes since early 1999. Thousands of people were either killed
or wounded and hundreds of public buildings destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid and other government
officials and military officers repeatedly said that the
government will reject foreign intervention in settling the
communal clashes in Maluku. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
