<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bashar to Visit Lebanon in Few Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Bashar al-Assad
will pay an official visit to Lebanon in the next few weeks as part
of an Arab tour that is expected to take him to Saudi Arabia,
Jordan, Egypt, Bahrain and other countries, An Nahar newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The tour is aimed at thanking the leaders of those countries for
the sympathy they expressed on the death of late Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad, who passed away on June 10.
</P>
<P>
Bashar's visit to Lebanon would be the first of its kind by a
serving Syrian head of state since 1975, when the late Hafez al-
Assad met with late Lebanese President Suleiman Frangie in a city
on the Beirut-Damascus highway.
</P>
<P>
The visit will underscore Syria's final recognition of Lebanon's
independent statehood and further boost Lebanese President Emile
Lahoud's regime, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud, along with Prime Minister Salim Hoss and Parliament
Speaker Nabih Berri, will go to the northern Syrian town of Qardaha
to hold talks with Bashar on Thursday, Asharq newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Hafez al-Assad, whose country is the major power broker in
Lebanon, had held 83 summit meetings with Lebanese presidents
during his lifetime on Syrian soil and only once on the Beirut-
Damascus highway. But the deceased leader is the first post-
independence Syrian president to formally recognize Lebanon as an
independent state.
</P>
<P>
Hafez al-Assad signed with former Lebanese President Elias
Hraoui in 1992 a Treaty of Brotherhood, Cooperation and
Coordination between the two neighboring republics.
</P>
<P>
Bashar, who was sworn in as Syria's 16th post-independence
president on Monday, had been put by his father in charge of
Syria's role in Lebanon in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Bashar's forthcoming visit, if it comes through, will serve as a
finalization of Syria's official recognition of Lebanon's
independence, An Nahar said.
</P>
<P>
Like Palestine and Jordan, Lebanon was part of Syria during the
500-year Ottoman occupation.
</P>
<P>
The visit will put an end to the contention that Syrian
presidents do not make official visits to Lebanon for fear that
they would be interpreted as a recognition of Lebanon's sovereignty
and independence from Syria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
