<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Securities Regulation Code Signed Into Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
signed into law Wednesday two economic bills designed to help the
country compete under the era of globalization and bring in more
investors into its capital market.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered during the ceremonial signing of the two
laws in the presidential palace, Estrada noted that the enactment
of the investor-friendly New Securities Regulation Code represents
"a historic and positive turning point for the economic
development of our country."
</P>
<P>
The law empowers the government to completely reorganize the
Securities and Exchange Commission to enable it to address
changing market conditions.
</P>
<P>
"This new code should be a major engine to fuel our economic
growth and enable the Philippines to effectively compete in the
new global securities market and attract new investors," he said.
</P>
<P>
The bill seeking a new securities act was filed five years ago
during the Ramos administration, but was signed into law only
during the term of President Estrada, who urged Congress to give
priority to the measure "in recognition of the importance of the
capital market to sustainable economic growth."
</P>
<P>
The other measure signed into law, the Safeguard Measures
Against Import Surge Act, is expected to provide relief to
domestic industries as the country prepares for global competition.
</P>
<P>
Estrada explained that the Safeguard Measures Act allows the
government to impose additional tariffs on certain imports when
these increase in significant quantities and threaten domestic
industries.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from trade remedy measures which provide an adjustment
period for agriculture industries to become competitive, the law
also proposes adjustment plans for the affected sectors to adopt
in aid of enhancing competitiveness," he added.
</P>
<P>
The president lauded Congress for the early passage of the
measure, saying it is a welcome development for Filipino farmers "
growing sensitive agriculture products."
</P>
<P>
"The passage of this law is timely for the agriculture sector
as domestic producers are currently facing severe competition from
foreign imports which have been increasing over the last year or
so," he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concern over the surge in imports of such
commodities as chicken parts, onion and garlic and other food
items, which has seriously threatened the local agriculture
industry.
</P>
<P>
The president stressed that the enactment of the Safeguard
Measures and the Securities Regulation Code provide a component
necessary to build a modernized framework for business "that
should enable our economy to surge ahead once they are fully
implemented."
</P>
<P>
The two economic measures were passed by Congress on Monday,
the first of its two-day special session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
