<HEADLINE> 27 Al-Ma'unah Members Remanded for Two More Weeks in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The 27 men belonging to the
Al-Ma'unah deviant group which planned the arms heist in Malaysia
earlier this month have been remanded for a further two weeks to
facilitate police investigations, Bernama news agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 27 were first remanded on July 7 to enable police to
investigate them for alleged involvement in armed robbery from two
military camps in Gerik in the northern state of Perak on July 2
and in taking four hostages -- a durian collector, a soldier and
two police personnel.
</P>
<P>
The fresh remand orders were issued Wednesday by the magistrate
in Kuala Kangsar and in Ipoh in the state respectively, where the
27 were separately remanded, to allow police to probe them for
allegedly abducting people, Bernama said.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen of the 27 men are alleged to have staged the arms
heist together with another gang member who was killed in the
crossfire with securities forces during a five-day standoff.
</P>
<P>
The 27 men were accused of holding four men as hostages and
killing two of them before surrendering on July 6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
