<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladeshi Government Forms Committee to Prevent Dengue Fever (By Pan Xiaozhu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Government formed a high-
powered committee Tuesday for preventing and monitoring the dengue
attacks, as residents of Dhaka city are scared of the spread of
dengue fever at an alarming rate and rise in dengue deaths during
the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
An inter-ministerial meeting with Health Minister Sheikh Fazlul
Karim Selim in the chair decided Tuesday to destroy the breeding
abodes of mosquito in order to combat spread of dengue fever in
the city.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also asked the authorities concerned for
strengthening preventive measures and monitoring the situation
round the clock.
</P>
<P>
At least eight people have died and over 100 people with dengue
fever were admitted to hospitals in the city in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The scare aggravated as an expert last week said there was no
treatment of the dengue fever in the country.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Nazrul Islam, an expert on virology at the Bangabandhu
Sheikh Mujib Medical University, warned that unless spread of the
mosquito which carries the disease, was checked, the situation
could be worse soon.
</P>
<P>
Many panic stricken people in the capital, who usually do not
use mosquito nets and depended on anti-mosquito smokes and liquid
sprays, are now queuing in shops to buy nets to protect them from
the deadly virus fever.
</P>
<P>
The country's only government laboratory reportedly uses
reagents that have mostly expired, for tests to detect dengue
attacks. The equipment of the laboratory are also out-dated. The
laboratory relies on the kits from the World Health Organization (
WHO) to conduct tests. What is more appalling is that there are no
enough scientists to conduct emergency surveys if ever required.
</P>
<P>
The WHO informed the health ministry Tuesday that it has taken
an initiative to train about 90 doctors, both from public and
private sectors in the country. Moreover, it would provide 1000
more test kits to the Health Directorate for dengue tests while a
surveillance team to assess the dengue situation in Bangladesh is
due here shortly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Garment Industry Prepares to Face Quota-Free Era </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's garment industry has
been urged to speed up their adjustments to face quota-free era
beginning from 2005 when quotas are completely phased out, an
official with the Textile Quota Board (TQB) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said some garment manufacturers were exporting to the
European Union (EU) without a quota and were working towards a non-
quota era.
</P>
<P>
The garment industry has risen to be one of the most important
sectors in Sri Lanka's export economy in the last two decades and
is the largest industrial employment sector with over 350,000
employed directly.
</P>
<P>
However, the industry has for long enjoyed the security
provided by the Multi-Fibre Agreement (MFA) for garment exports to
industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
With the phasing out of the MFA in 2005, those manufacturers
who were dependent on quotas may face increased competition and
will require more aggressive marketing to win orders.
</P>
<P>
The TQB also informed garment exporters to stick to 2003 as the
target year to diversify markets worldwide to reduce the
dependence on the United States and the European Union (EU) which
together account for over 90 percent of the island's garment
exports.
</P>
<P>
Recently the European Commission proposed to liberalize textile
and clothing imports from January 2002, eliminating all remaining
restrictions on imports of 62 categories of textiles and clothing
products from other countries belonging to the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
The TQB is hopeful that Sri Lanka garment industry will benefit
from Europe's imports liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The EU is the second largest biggest market for Sri Lankan
garment exports after the United States. Just over 60 percent of
garment exports go to the United States and 34 percent to the EU,
mainly the United Kingdom and Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
