<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Istanbul will host the 23rd International Shoe Fashion
Fair on July 20-23, reported Anatolia News Agency Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The fair, organized by Turkey Shoe Industrialists Association,
is expected to bring together 206 shoe firms from Turkey, Greece,
Italy, Germany, Belgium, Tunisia, Sweden and Croatia as well as
China's Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of wholesale shoe manufacturers from Greece and
Israel will have contacts both at the fair and at shoe
manufacturing ateliers to purchase shoes.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The Thomas Cook Group, the British tour giant, is
ready to proceed with large investments in Cyprus, the Financial
Mirror newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Simon Vincent, chief operating officer of Thomas Cook Group, has
openly invited hotel groups and land developers to discuss the
possibility of cooperating with his group in new projects in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Vincent said his group is making efforts to convert Cyprus into
a 12-month tourist destination and therefore it is planning to
launch winter flights to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Thomas Cook Group is the largest British tour operator in
North America and has one of the largest retailers of money
exchange because it holds the exclusive rights to a number of
international airports in this area.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- U.S. power concern InterGen and Turkish company Enka
will lay the foundation of a gas-generated power plant in
Adapazari, northwest of Turkey, on Wednesday, reported Anatolia
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The InterGen-Enka consortium will build and operate the plant
which has an installed capacity of 770 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
The build-own-operate (BOO) project will be financed by both
domestic and foreign private capital.
</P>
<P>
InterGen and Enka have also taken on contracts to build two
other gas-fired power plants in Gebze and Izmir in western Turkey.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Trade exchanges between Cyprus and Russia are
characterized by an imbalance to the benefit of Russia, the
Financial Mirror newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' total imports from Russia in 1999 amounted to almost 59
million Cyprus pounds (118 million U.S. dollars) whereas total
exports reached 35.3 million pounds (70.6 million dollars), out of
which only 1.4 million pounds (2.8 million dollars) were domestic
exports.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' domestic exports to Russia gradually decreased every
year during the period of 1997 to 1999, mainly due to the
deteriorating economic situation that prevailed in Russia during
1998-1999, but also to the fierce competition that Cyprus has to
face from other countries.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the economic crisis in Russia, tourist arrivals
in Cyprus declined by 32 percent in 1999 as only 134,000 tourists
visited Cyprus compared to 197,500 in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
