<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Next Few Hours Critical for Camp David Summit: Israeli Delegate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The coming few hours will be
critical for reaching an Israeli-Palestinian peace deal at Camp
David in the United States, a senior Israeli delegate to the summit
told Israel Radio Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Haifa Mayor Amnon Mitzne, who was summoned early this week by
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak to join in the Israeli delegation
at Camp David, said that certain "understandings" have been reached
at the summit, which was attended by Barak, Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat, and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which entered into the 10th day Wednesday, aimed to
resolve core issues between the two sides, such as the fate of
Jerusalem, Palestinian refugees, Jewish settlement, borders,
security and water.
</P>
<P>
Mitzne, who was former Israel Defense Forces' Central Commander,
confirmed that marathon talks between Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators are continuing in the hope of reaching an agreement
prior to Clinton's departure for Japan on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has announced early Wednesday that he will postpone his
planned departure from Wednesday to Thursday for the G-8 economic
summit in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Mitzne admitted that although he is a formal delegate, he could
not participate in the core summit directly. So he could only get
limited accurate information because of the media blackout
exercised by the U.S..
</P>
<P>
However, Mitzne stressed that as far as he knows, Barak still
maintains his famous five "red lines," namely:
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem will remain united and under Israeli sovereignty;
</P>
<P>
There will be no return to the pre-June 1967 borders;
</P>
<P>
No foreign army will be stationed west of the Jordan River;
</P>
<P>
Israel does not agree to a blanket "right of return" for
Palestinians displaced in 1948 and 1967 wars;
</P>
<P>
And a majority of the Israeli settlements in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip will remain under Israeli sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Mitzne also revealed that he believed an agreement reached at
Camp David might not be "black and white", but a partial deal or an
agreement to return to another summit session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
