<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Takes High Toll on Teachers in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 19 (Xinhua) -- An estimated 860,000 children in
black Africa lost their teachers to AIDS in 1999, says a report
released by the U.N. Children's Fund (Unicef).
</P>
<P>
The Unicef report, released here Tuesday, adds that children
in Kenya, Nigeria and South Africa are most affected by these
losses.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, for example, every 95,000 primary school children
lost a teacher to the scourge last year, the report says, adding
that "for reasons not entirely clear, HIV is very high among
teachers and school administrators".
</P>
<P>
Although HIV/AIDS affects all sectors, the report says, its
most profound effects are felt in education.
</P>
<P>
The report points out that hard-won gains in school enrollment
and return on investments in education are now being eroded by the
disease in all over black Africa.
</P>
<P>
Schooling is disrupted when teachers are absent from class due
to illness, death or the need to care for ill family members, and
HIV-positive teachers are leaving schools in remote areas lacking
health care facilities or asking for posting in locations near
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
"National efforts to develop school-based programs to control
HIV/AIDS have been dealt a mortal blow and assistance from the
international community is urgently needed," the report calls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
