<HEADLINE> U.S. Shooting Suspect Boy Gives Himself up to Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A 13-year-old boy, suspected
of pulling the trigger in his school cafeteria, turned himself in
to police, a spokesman for local Sheriff's Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The boy, Josh Warnock, was taken into custody at the home of
his grandparents, six blocks from his middle School near Seattle,
where police said he fired one shot from a .22-caliber handgun
into the ceiling of the cafeteria, but no one was injured.
</P>
<P>
The boy spent Monday night "in woods" near his grandparents'
home 10 miles south of Seattle, sheriff's spokesman John Urquhart
said. His mother notified authorities that her son wanted to give
himself up to the police, so that the boy was arrested peacefully
at his grandparents' house.
</P>
<P>
Warnock was booked into a juvenile detention in Seattle for
investigation of assault with a firearm and reckless endangerment.
</P>
<P>
The motive for the shooting remained unclear, and the gun,
which authorities say belonged to the boy's grandfather, had not
yet been recovered, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Warnock may be charged with unlawful possession of a firearm.
The boy's initial court hearing was scheduled for Wednesday, and
prosecutors were requesting that he be held until then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
