<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alert Issued Against Excessive Algae in South Korean River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Seoul Municipality Wednesday
issued an alert against excessive algae in the Han River, the
second largest river of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The municipality said the alert covers all parts of the Han
River between the eastern Kangdong Bridge and far western Haengju
Bridge, as the water contains standard-exceeding amounts of algae.
</P>
<P>
The water in the river was found to contain 25 mg of type A
chlorophyll per cubic meters of water and 2,027 cells of blue
algae per milliliter.
</P>
<P>
An alert is usually issued when the density of type A
chlorophyll exceeds 15 mg per cubic meters of water and the cells
of blue algae number 500 or more per milliliter.
</P>
<P>
The density of algae in the river has recently risen to those
high levels due to the unusually dry rainy season, said the
municipality.
</P>
<P>
The city administration plans to destroy the algae by spraying
loess and to keep water-purifying facilities under close watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corrupt Swiss Companies to Lose Government Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Swiss Economics Minister Pascal
Couchepin has warned that Swiss companies guilty of corrupt
dealings abroad may lose the export risk guarantees (ERG) they
receive from the government, media reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the development aid group, the Berne Declaration,
Couchepin welcomed the tighter anti-corruption law introduced on
May 1. His statement, made public on Tuesday, came in response to
an accusation by the Berne Declaration in June that officials in
the department were trying to block Indonesia's corruption probe
into Switzerland's dealings with the former Suharto regime.
</P>
<P>
The minister supported the arguments advanced by the department
responsible for issuing ERGs that exporters had to ensure they
complied with the law. At the same time, officials should withdraw
or withhold payments if companies were found to be involved in
corruption, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Couchepin insisted that export companies were
responsible for their own dealings, and it was not the job of his
ministry to make sure they stayed within the law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
