<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Only Taiyuan reported slight air
pollution today, with pollutant indicator reading at 125.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily air quality report issued by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center today, level-two, or fairly good
air quality, was found in the following 28 cities: Beijing,
Tianjin, Shijiazhuang, Hohhot, Shenyang, Changchun, Shanghai,
Nanjing, Suzhou, Nantong, Hangzhou, Wenzhou, Hefei, Jinan,
Zhengzhou, Wuhan, Changsha, Guangzhou, Zhanjiang, Chongqing,
Chengdu, Guiyang, Kunming, Xi'an, Lanzhou, Xining, Yinchuan and
Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
Particulate matter less than 10 microns in size was the major
pollutant in most of the cities, except Nanning, Chongqing and
Guiyang, where sulfur dioxide was the major air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen cities, namely, Dalian, Harbin, Fuzhou, Xiamen,
Nanchang, Qingdao, Yantai, Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Shantou, Nanning,
Haikou and Lhasa, reported excellent air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level-one or excellent (pollution readings: not
exceeding 50), level-two or fairly good (pollution readings: 51 to
100), level-three or slightly polluted (pollution readings: 101-
200), level-four or poor (pollution readings: 201 to 300) and
level-five or hazardous (pollution readings: over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored include the four municipalities of
Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing, provincial capitals, and
major cities in the economically developed coastal area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Retirees Get Pensions From Social Security Bodies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Along with the ongoing reform of
social security system, more and more Chinese retirees are
receiving their pensions from social security bodies via post
offices or banks, instead of being paid by their former working
units.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this June, 18.56 million Chinese retirees, or 64
percent of the total, got their pensions from social security
departments, 4,887,000 people more or 15.8 percentage points
higher than the figures of the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Labor and Social Security, the
social security bodies deposit the money into the bank account of
each of the retirees monthly, so as to ensure timely payment of
their pensions.
</P>
<P>
In some areas including Shanghai Municipality, in east China,
and Shaanxi Province, in the northwest, 100 percent of the
retirees obtain their pensions from their accounts at local banks
or post offices.
</P>
<P>
However, the percentage is quite low in some places, such as
Beijing, the national capital, 30.7 percent; underdeveloped
southwestern Guizhou Province, 30.6 percent; southern Hunan
Province, 21.7 percent; and northeastern Jilin Province, where
there are lots of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has urged these areas to reach the goal set by the
State Council--to distribute 100 percent of pensions by social
security departments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
