<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- As the negotiations at Camp David entered a critical stage
Tuesday night, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak indicated to
confidants that he believes a deal is possible, despite reports
that the talks were collapsing over the issue of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Most media speculation Tuesday focused on Jerusalem, with
reports claiming that the compromise being discussed would involve
Jerusalem's borders being expanded to bring settlements Ma'aleh
Adumim, Givat Ze'ev, and Gush Etzion under full Israeli
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
In return, the Palestinians would gain control over Arab
neighborhoods in and around east Jerusalem. They would also get
control over the Muslim and Christian holy sites in the Old City,
and would be allowed to fly their flag over Al-Aqsa Mosque, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- In withering talks described by one Israeli as a "war of
attrition," Israeli and Palestinian negotiators have reached a
range of understandings on a new, American-mediated package of
proposals on the core issues of borders, refugees and Jerusalem,
but they still await the approval of Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton is prepared to delay his planned
departure for the G-8 summit in Japan until Thursday morning in
order to give a final push toward an accord.
</P>
<P>
If Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak reach an
agreement, a framework deal outlining the principles of a final
peace treaty will be signed Thursday at the White House.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Two early-election bills will be brought to Israel's Knesset
(Parliament) for a preliminary reading on August 2. In an
unexpected move, Knesset Speaker Avraham Burg Tuesday arranged for
action on this bill for the dissolution of the Knesset and early
elections in advance of the Knesset's summer recess.
</P>
<P>
Burg's move is surprising as Knesset regulations stipulate that
resumed action on such bills cannot be taken for at least six
months after it fails in a Knesset vote. However, Burg said Tuesday
that "there has been a real change in circumstances, and so there
is no need to wait six months before discussing dissolution
proposals."
</P>
<P>
Burg said that he notified Prime Minister Ehud Barak at Camp
David of his decision, and that Minister in Prime Minister's Office
Haim Ramon and other One Israel ruling coalition leaders do not
oppose the schedule.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- The Knesset (Parliament) Labor and Welfare Committee decided
Tuesday to bring a bill calling for an increase in state funding
for large families to its second and third readings.
</P>
<P>
The bill would raise the grant for each child from the fifth
onward to NIS 2,400 (about 587 U.S. dollars). A family with five
children would also receive an additional five points on the scale
of aid given to large families, which would translate into an
increase of NIS 850 (about 208 dollars) for each child.
</P>
<P>
Secular legislators vehemently blasted the bill, as the secular
families carry the major burden of the child allowance, but the
ultra-Orthodox families, which usually have more than five
children, just benefit from the state funding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
