<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Qatar to Enhance Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Qatar have decided to
upgrade their present relations to the highest possible level, said
a joint communique issued here late Tuesday at the end of a two-day
visit to Iran by Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa Al-Thani.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, the two countries expressed their support for
investment cooperation, particularly in the private sector, and
stressed that promoting such cooperation would contribute to the
development of the Iranian-Qatari ties.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also underscored the need for cooperation among
all countries in the Persian Gulf to safeguard peace and security
in the region, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hamad, the first Qatari head of state that has visited
Iran since the 1979 Islamic revolution, spoke highly of President
Mohammad Khatami's policy to broaden relations with Gulf states,
and expressed hope that exchange of state visits between Gulf
countries would promote mutual confidence.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, Iran and Qatar also clarified their stands on
such issues as the Middle East peace, Iraq, Afghanistan and oil
price.
</P>
<P>
They expressed support for the Palestinian people, and condemned
the oppressive policies of Israel, which they described as being in
contravention of international diplomatic norms.
</P>
<P>
They condemned the further expansion of Jewish settlements on
the occupied territories, and voiced their opposition to any "
scheme" for transforming the "Islamic and Arab identity" of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The two countries stressed the need to put an end to Israel's
occupation of all Palestinian territories, and underscored the
rights of Palestinians, including their rights for self-
determination and for establishing an independent government.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed their full support for the stance of Syria
on the issue of Golan Heights that are currently under Israeli
occupation.
</P>
<P>
They voiced their concern about Israel's production of weapons
of mass destruction, and called on all countries in the region to
abide by the nuclear non-proliferation treaty.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, the two countries expressed their sympathy
with the Iraqi people, and stressed that the time has come for
lifting the U.N. sanctions on Iraq in keeping with the resolutions
of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Afghanistan, the communique stressed the urgency
for returning peace and security to that country through dialogs
among different factions.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Qatar condemned all forms of terrorism, but called for
discriminating between terrorist groups and national resistance
movements that fight occupiers of their homelands, the communique
said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also reviewed the current situation of the oil
market, and underscored the need for all member states of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to cooperate
in stabilizing oil market so that the interests of producers and
consumers are equally considered.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari emir started his visit on Monday accompanied by
several high-ranking officials, including Foreign Minister Sheikh
Hamad Bin Jabir Al-Thani and Minister of Finance, Economy and Trade
Yousef Hussein Kamal.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Sheikh Hamad held separate meetings with
President Khatami, the supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei,
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi as well as Iranian Defense
Minister Ali Shamkhani on broadening cooperation in various fields.
Several cooperation agreements were also signed during the visit.
</P>
<P>
After years of mutual suspicion caused by the 1979 Islamic
revolution, Iran and its Gulf Arab neighbors have improved ties in
recent years, especially since President Khatami took office in
1997. Khatami paid landmark visits to Saudi Arabia and Qatar in
April 1999, which opened a new chapter for their ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
