<HEADLINE> Dutch Police Release Fireworks Staff After Probe in May Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch law enforcement
department released seven of the staff of the Enschede fireworks
company late on Tuesday, two months after police detained them for
a May 13 explosion that claimed 18 lives in the eastern Dutch town
of Enschede, the Belgium television reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The seven people admitted having illegally sold fireworks to
individuals in the Netherlands and two of them declared that the
two directors of the fireworks firm were spotted irregularities
with the storage of the fireworks, according to television reports.
</P>
<P>
The fireworks company, located right in the middle of a
residential area of Enschede, exploded in the late afternoon of
May 13. A fire was suspected to have caused a smaller blast which
coaxed local residents to gather around the fireworks with the
belief that a fireworks show was on.
</P>
<P>
A second bigger explosion soon ensued only to kill and wound
onlookers and passers-by, burn cars and destroy houses close to
the fireworks company.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch and neighboring German firefighters had to come to
the rescue of Enschede residents.
</P>
<P>
A long list of people listed as missing puzzled the rescuers
who dug through the rubbles for days to try to find out anyone
still buried in the aftermath of the explosion.
</P>
<P>
Some critics said that those listed as missing from the
explosion could well be illegal immigrants from elsewhere and they
had to move away in a fear that they would otherwise be spotted
with a national limelight turned on the town.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok went to inspect the disaster area
the next day after the explosion and the Dutch government has
released a special aid fund for the town. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
