<HEADLINE> Dozen U.S. Residents Killed in Week-long Heat Wave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The week-long heat wave has
been blamed for the deaths of 12 Texas residents, according to
reports reaching late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Heat-related deaths were reported in Houston, Dallas, Austin of
Texas state and Shreveport of Louisiana state. Several of the
victims were elderly shut-ins who had no air conditioners or could
not afford the electricity to keep the units running, officials
were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
An emergency health alert is now in place in the Dallas-Fort
Worth area, where 100 degree plus temperatures have lingered for a
week.
</P>
<P>
The emergency declaration also prohibits utility companies from
cutting off service to late-paying customers.
</P>
<P>
More than 120 towns and cities in Texas have water restrictions
because of drought. Residents in the north-central town of
Throckmorton are racing to get a 25-kilometer water pipeline in
place before the town's sole water supply dries up, likely in
about two months.
</P>
<P>
No relief was expected anytime soon from the heat wave which is
also baking states like Arizona and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Unrelenting sun prompted the National Weather Service to issue
heat advisories for much of Texas, Oklahoma, Arkansas, Louisiana
and Mississippi, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
