<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand to Open New Nuclear Test Monitoring Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
announced in a Wednesday's press release that it will open a new
nuclear monitoring station on Friday at Kaitaia in the
Northernmost part of New Zealand's North Island.
</P>
<P>
The state-of-the-art station, which costs 400,000 U.S. dollars,
monitors radionuclide activity or the minute particles of
radioactive dust released into the atmosphere by nuclear
explosions.
</P>
<P>
It is one of the three monitoring stations operated by New
Zealand and will eventually have the ability to detect radioactive
gases and very longwave infrasound waves throughout the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The station, which was officially connected to the
international network in March, is part of the international
Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty which will see more than 300
international monitoring stations set up world-wide to prevent
nuclear testing being performed in secret and in breach of the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
Four technologies (radionuclide, infrasound, seismic and
hydroacoustic) will be used in a chain of monitoring stations
around the world to detect explosions regardless of whether the
blasts are underground, under the sea or in the air.
</P>
<P>
The Kaitaia station is strategically important for the treaty
because it can monitor large parts of the Pacific Ocean, according
to the press release.
</P>
<P>
The other two stations operated by New Zealand are located in
the Chatham Islands, which is 800 kilometers from New Zealand's
east coast, and in the Cook Islands.
</P>
<P>
All the three stations are equipped with sophisticated
radionuclide detection equipment imported from the United States
and Germany, and will use a New Zealand-developed software program
to communicate with the International Data Center in Vienna.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Imposes Sanctions on Fiji </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Fijian military personnel in
New Zealand are being sent home and a ban on sporting contacts
with Fiji has been extended, according to a New Zealand government
announcement.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Prime Minister Helen Clark announced the measures
here Wednesday afternoon and promised there would be more to come
unless "there are firm signs of a return to democracy" in the
troubled island nation.
</P>
<P>
The measures came after the announcement Tuesday night of the
line-up of a new Fijian government, which contains a number of
supporters of coup leader George Speight.
</P>
<P>
"The ministerial line-up announced last night not only
contained Speight supporters, but also was clearly
unrepresentative of Fiji. It was to replace a government which did
have mandate derived from general elections held under the Fiji
constitution," the New Zealand prime minister said in the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
While that administration has yet to be sworn in, the further
delays in the formation of a government are yet more evidence that
Fiji will be "in a state of uncertainty" for some time to come,
Clark said.
</P>
<P>
The measures announced Wednesday will see 41 Fijian military
personnel currently with the New Zealand Army and Navy sent home
within a week, as well as the recall of two New Zealand defense
force personnel from Fiji.
</P>
<P>
And a ban on sporting contacts covering individuals, national
and club sides deemed to be representing Fiji has been extended to
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday night, the New Zealand government announced that it was
recalling the New Zealand High Commissioner in Suva for
consultations in response to the inclusion of Speight supporters
in the new government.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week the government cut defense ties and halved
aid to Fiji,but held off on further measures till the new Fijian
government was revealed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
