<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's White Farmers Withdraw Offer of 180 farms for Resettlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's commercial farmers have
withdrawn their offer of 180 farms for the country's resettlement
program in protest against the compulsory acquisition of farms by
the government without paying compensation, The Herald newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Commercial Farmers' Union (CFU) had offered the farms,
outside the 804 targeted for compulsory acquisition, for the
implementation of the fast-track approach to land reform and
resettlement.
</P>
<P>
Of the 804 that had been earmarked for acquisition, 445 had
been contested, 71 had been appealed for while there was no
response from the owners of 59 others.
</P>
<P>
"We contested the compulsory acquisition of the 445 farms
because we do not believe farms can just be taken away without
paying compensation," CFU President Tim Henwood said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Launching the fast-track resettlement program last week to
start resettling landless blacks on 200 of 804 white-owned farms,
Vice-President Joseph Msika said the CFU had provided a summary
table of 180 farms with no names or an indication of their precise
location.
</P>
<P>
With the government having amended the constitution to allow
acquiring land without paying compensation, owners of the 804
farms can only appeal against the move.
</P>
<P>
Contesting the acquisition of the properties would not produce
the desired results as the government would still go ahead and
take the farms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Military Begins to Investigate Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean Defense Ministry
Wednesday started its probe into a scandal on excessive payments
for plane fuel over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday morning, Defense Minister Cho Sung-tae ordered an
investigation team to thoroughly probe into the allegation.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean Board of Audit and Inspection ordered the
ministry early this month to retrieve some 120 billion won (about
100 million U.S. dollars) in excessive payments for oil that it
purchased from refineries in 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
The amount is about 45 percent of the 271 billion won (about
225.8 million dollars) that the ministry should have paid for the
gasoline and diesel for military use in 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
In a report, the board said the ministry paid 261.4 billion won
(about 217.8 million dollars) for 931.4 million liters of gasoline
for airplanes in 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
The ministry paid 280.65 won (about 25 cents) per liter, 92.23
won (about eight cents) higher than the price Korean Air and other
airlines paid for their gasoline.
</P>
<P>
The investigation team will call in military procurement
officials in charge of purchasing plane fuel and diesel from five
domestic refineries for questioning, said the Defense Ministry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
