<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paraguay Stun Brazil in World Cup Qualifier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Paraguay stunned Brazil in a
soccer World Cup qualifier on Tuesday by beating the four-times
champions 2-1.
</P>
<P>
It was Brazil's second ever defeat in a World Cup qualifier --
their first bitter experience was against Bolivia in 1993 -- and
the win gave Paraguay nine points, while Brazil had only eight.
</P>
<P>
Paraguay's first goal came in sixth minute from Carlos Paredes.
Substitute Jorge Campos scored a decisive goal in the 83rd minute,
nine minutes after Rivaldo's goal which seemed to save the world
champion's face.
</P>
<P>
Brazil made five changes to the team which drew 1-1 with
Uruguay last month. At the early stage of the game, Edmilson and
Roque Junior seemed comfortable at the heart of Brazil's
reorganized defense, but both were responsible for Paredes's
header.
</P>
<P>
Trailing 1-0 behind, Brazil continued to lack confidence and
were unable to find any rhythm. Brazil's situations even worsened
shortly before the break, when Cafu was dismissed for a second
yellow card offense after pole-axing Paredes.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian coach Wanderley Luxemburgo, still searching for an
effective attacking formula to fill the gap left by Ronaldo who is
suffering from long-term knee injury, sent on Guilherme for Franca
at half-time but the change didn't work.
</P>
<P>
But the 1999 World Player Rivaldo stooped to head a Roberto
Carlos cross past Chilavert in the 74th minute.
</P>
<P>
Brazil were seemingly in a better position when Paraguay
substitute Victor Quintana was also sent off for a dangerous
tackle on Roberto Carlos in the 79th minute, having been on the
field for only 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
However, Campos drove the home fans crazy when he wrapped up
the victory by sweeping the ball past Brazilian goalkeeper Dida.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's result could lead to speculation about the future of
coach Luxemburgo.
</P>
<P>
Brazil will meet arch-rivals Argentina next week, and the four-
time world champions now are in desperate need of winning the game
to restore confidence in the team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
