<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Liberalize Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- China will liberalize the interest
rates system in about three years, said Dai Xianglong, Governor
the People's Bank of China, at a press conference held today.
</P>
<P>
Dai said that the country does plan to liberalize the interest
rates. So far, the interest rates for foreign currencies and those
for inter-bank lending have been opened.
</P>
<P>
The next move will be liberalizing the lending interest rates
in rural areas. "For the urban areas, we will first widen the
floating extent of loans."
</P>
<P>
As for the deposits, interest rates of wholesale deposits will
first be opened and other kinds of deposits will follow.
</P>
<P>
After liberalization of the interest rates, bank associations
will play a more important role in supervision and management. The
PBOC will strengthen management through refinancing and open
market.
</P>
<P>
"All these can be fulfilled in three years, and liberalization
of interest rates for deposits should be cautious," said Dai.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
