<HEADLINE> Manila Launches Program for Disabled Persons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
launched a warm-hearted project to help assist the country's
disabled persons in every possible way, the Philippine News Agency
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Health Secretary Alberto Romualdez was quoted as saying that
the project, dubbed "Drop an Aid," aims to help disabled persons
get back into the mainstream of society considering that there is
a higher mortality and morbidity on this group.
</P>
<P>
In the observance of the 22nd National Disability Prevention
and Rehabilitation Week, Romualdez urged people to donate
wheelchairs, crutches, canes, hearing aids, etc., to help indigent
disabled persons.
</P>
<P>
The "Drop an Aid" project will later be expanded to all
government-run regional hospitals, retained hospitals and medical
centers. These hospitals will serve as store room for all donated
technical aids, he added.
</P>
<P>
The government statistics show that the country's disabled
persons have mounted to an estimated 7.4 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
