<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharp U.S. Economic Slowdown in 2001 Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 18 (Xinhua) -- An American business
membership and research organization, for the first time in
several years, Tuesday forecast a sharp decline in U.S. economic
growth beginning during the summer of next year.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board said in a report that real GDP is expected
to fall to an annual rate of two percent by mid-2001, down from an
anticipated five percent and 4.2 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The organization's Leading Economic Indicators and various
measures of business profitability clearly point to further
Federal Reserve Board action and future economic weakness, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
"While higher interest rates have forced down many stock
valuations, they have had little impact on the total liquidity
available in the marketplace," the report said. "The Federal
Reserve Board's efforts to contain the economy will tend to be
offset by this additional liquidity that is financing ventures
that would have been subject to Fed restraints in the past."
</P>
<P>
Although signs of slowing in the U.S. economy have become more
pronounced since the beginning of June, the Conference Board said,
further Fed interest rate hikes are still likely. The heightened
volatility in financial markets reflects an ambivalence about
whether the Fed can accomplish its anti-inflation objectives and
bring better balance to the economy without something harmful
happening.
</P>
<P>
According to the research organization, the current slowdown is
unlikely to convince the Fed to reverse policy. The U.S. economy
has tremendous forward momentum and even though current trends are
cautionary, the economy is likely to re-accelerate by year-end,
prompting another series of Fed interest rate increases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
