<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Puts off Japan Trip for More Mediation in Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
early Wednesday postponed his planned trip to Japan by one day in
order to help Israelis and Palestinians search for a deal to end
their 52-year conflict, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
"The president regrets that he will have to delay his departure
to Japan for one day," White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told
reporters. "The president believes that this is in the best
interest of the Middle East peace process," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was originally scheduled to depart for Japan at 9:10 a.
m. EDT (1310 GMT) on Wednesday to attend a summit of
industrialized countries in Okinawa on July 21-13.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said that Clinton now will leave on Thursday and
arrive in Japan in time for the opening of the Okinawa summit on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The drastic move will give Clinton an extra day to try to
broker a peace agreement between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders have met in Camp David, a U.S. presidential
retreat in northern Maryland, since July 11 in a bid to break a
deadlock on final status issues between Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators.
</P>
<P>
Despite Clinton's hectic mediation over the past eight days,
Israelis and Palestinians have so far failed to strike a deal due
to differences on the core final status issues, especially the
status of Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul Proposes Inter-Korean Ministerial Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 19 (Xinhua) -- South Korea Wednesday proposed that
the ministerial talks in Seoul next week should discuss follow-up
measures to the inter-Korean summit agreement.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
Prime Minister Song-nam, South Korean Prime Minister Lee Han-dong
proposed that a 35-member delegation from each side would meet for
talks on July 27-29.
</P>
<P>
Each delegation will consist of five government officials, five
accompanying delegates, 10 reporters and 15 support team members,
the letter said.
</P>
<P>
The South-North Korean joint declaration signed by the top
leaders will serve as a milestone to the settlement of
reconciliation, cooperation and peaceful co-existence between the
two sides, Lee wrote in the letter.
</P>
<P>
"I believe it is the historic responsibility for us to honor
the intentions of the two leaders and implement the joint
declaration," said the South Korean prime minister.
</P>
<P>
South Korean President Kim Dae-jung and DPRK leader Kim Jong-il
met in the first-ever inter-Korean summit in Pyongyang last month
and signed the joint declaration on national unification.
</P>
<P>
Lee proposed the meeting in Seoul should be held as the summit
and Red Cross talks were done in the DPRK, said government sources.
</P>
<P>
If realized, the meeting will be the first within nearly nine
years.
</P>
<P>
The last inter-Korean ministerial talks were held in Seoul in
1992 when the prime ministers of the two sides met. 
</P>
</TEXT>
