<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Port Inefficiencies Cost Bangladesh 1.25 Billion Dollars Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Inefficiencies at Chittagong, the
largest port of Bangladesh, cost the country 1.25 billion U.S.
dollars per year, more than the net inflow of all foreign
assistance, The Daily Star reported here Wednesday, quoting
statistics of the American Chamber of Commerce (AmCham) in
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Identifying the port situation as a big problem for Bangladesh,
Forrest Cookson, President of the AmCham, said that delays and
rising costs of using the port are now serious threats to the
country's garment trade with the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We estimate that Bangladesh could gain 125 percent increase in
foreign exchange from garment exports if the port functions
smoothly," said Cookson.
</P>
<P>
Urging the Bangladeshi government to take immediate steps to
improve the port situation, the AmCham recommended for declaring
the port operations as essential services and stopping illegal
strikes.
</P>
<P>
The chamber also suggested keeping the port operative 24 hours
a day, seven days a week over the next six months and stopping the
illegal toll collection at the entry point of the port as well as
inside it.
</P>
<P>
Cookson urged the government to endorse the construction of the
proposed new container terminal to expand the country's capacity
of handling international trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Optimistic of Ending Maluku Conflicts Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
optimistic that the communal bloodshed in the country's Maluku and
North Maluku provinces could be ended soon, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"It takes time to control the situation. Hopefully, within next
one and a half month, the situation (in Maluku and North Maluku)
could be controlled. But to block the entering of outsiders and
prevent gun smuggling will take time," Minister of Defense Juwono
Sudarsono was quoted Wednesday by the Kompas daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister reiterated the government's position of opposing
any foreign intervention in settling communal conflict in Maluku,
saying that the central government is effectively handling the
situation there.
</P>
<P>
Previously, some religious leaders in the two provinces have
asked the government to invite international forces to help
restore security and order in the conflict area.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Churches Association (PGI) voiced its demands
for foreign intervention in Maluku and North Maluku conflicts "for
the sake of humanity." It also asked the United Nations, the
United States and the European community to urge the Indonesian
government to end what it called "a humanitarian tragedy in Maluku
and North Maluku provinces soon."
</P>
<P>
But President Abdurrahman Wahid reaffirmed that the government
opposed possible military intervention from foreign countries to
put an end to the bloodshed in the provinces, saying that as a
sovereign state, Indonesia is fully responsible for its domestic
affairs and it had taken several measures to end the conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"Only when we are overwhelmed, maybe we will scream for
logistics and equipment. It is the maximum that we can accept,"
Wahid said.
</P>
<P>
Maluku and North Maluku provinces have witnessed a more than 18-
month communal bloodshed involving Muslims and Christians. The
bloodshed claimed thousands of lives and forced thousands of
others to take shelter in the neighboring provinces.
</P>
<P>
In its bid to stop the violence, the Indonesian government has
imposed a state of civil emergency and a curfew in the two
provinces last month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, opposition against foreign interventions in the
conflicts also came from Indonesian Police (Polri) and military (
TNI).
</P>
<P>
"We are very serious. You see several reactions from the two
warring camps (in Maluku). And we don't want to see the presence
of international troops (in Maluku) which in fact cannot solve the
problem, but create new problem. This is what we don't want (to
see)," spokesman of the TNI Rear Marshal Graito Usodo was quoted
as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
