<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Reports Lowest Crime Rate in 20 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Canada's national crime rate fell
five percent last year to 7,733 incidents for every 100,000 people,
the lowest level in the past two decades, Statistics Canada
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The statistics based on police data also show an eighth
consecutive annual drop in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Among Canada's 13 provinces and territories, Newfoundland had
the lowest rate of 5,921 crime incidents for every 100,000 people,
while Saskatchewan had the highest with 12,155 incidents reported
for every 100,000.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the country saw a drop of 7.2 percent in youth
crime in 1999, compared with the previous year, and a decline of
21 percent since 1989.
</P>
<P>
The national drop of youth crime was significantly contributed
by the country's three largest provinces, of which, Quebec
reported 7.8 percent off the previous year's figure, Ontario saw a
decline of 7.4 percent and British Columbia recorded a drop of 4.9
percent from the level one year ago.
</P>
<P>
Violent crime also fell 2.4 percent to 291,000 incidents in
1999, the seventh consecutive year of decline.  
</P>
</TEXT>
