<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Military Admits Troops Taking Sides in Conflicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Defense Forces (TNI)
has admitted that certain troops have taken sides in the long-
running Christian-Muslim war in the Maluku islands, but it flatly
denies involvement as an institution.
</P>
<P>
TNI Spokesman Rear Air Marshall Graito Usodo said Tuesday that
some soldiers have become emotionally involved in the sectarian
conflicts, but he denied involvement of the military as an
institution in the conflicts, the Indonesian Observer daily
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Some members of the military have reacted emotionally, either
because of their family names or where they come from," he said. "
This is inevitable and we admit the existence of these cases."
</P>
<P>
Usodo said that it was not the defense forces' policy to favor
one side over the other.
</P>
<P>
The TNI spokesman regretted calls by some circles here for
foreign intervention in the sectarian conflicts in Maluku, adding
that the TNI believed the conflict could be settled by Indonesians
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Defense Minister Juwono Sudarsono called on TNI
Commander Admiral Widodo to punish army troops involved in
disturbances on Ambon and to put an end to the religious violence.
</P>
<P>
Sudarsono said the warring factions have become tired of the
continuing fighting and would like to patch up their troubles and
establish peace. However, it would be necessary that positive
actions should be taken against those troublemakers so that they
could no longer be able to fan the members of religious conflict.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to halt the bloodshed, the government imposed a
state of civil emergency last month. But the move did little to
diffuse fierce street battles over the weekend that left almost 30
people dead.
</P>
<P>
Usodo said the military intends to send another infantry
battalion to the region, which would boost troops numbers to more
than 11,000.
</P>
<P>
In a fresh conflict Tuesday, two people were shot and killed by
snipers in Ambon, capital of Maluku province.
</P>
<P>
About 3000 people have been killed in Maluku and North Maluku
provinces since the fighting began in January 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
