<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lanka's Tourism Earns Some 1 Billion U.S. Dollars in Six Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's tourism sector has
earned 79 billion rupees (some 1 billion U.S. dollars) in foreign
exchange during the past six years, the official Daily News said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Tourism and Civil Aviation Dharmasiri Senanayake
was quoted as saying that the industry had also generated 87,600
direct and indirect employment opportunities during this period.
</P>
<P>
He said that this was no small feat given the constraints the
government and industry had faced especially with the ongoing
conflict and the false propaganda carried out by the Tamil Tiger
rebels who are waging a 17-year separatist war in Sri Lanka's
north and east.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that timely and effective development
policies along with incentives provided by the state were
instrumental in promoting the tourism.
</P>
<P>
Senanayake's appointment as Chairman of the World Tourism
Organization's Executive Council is also considered to have
fortified the focus of world attention on Sri Lanka's tourism
potential.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka, known as the Pearl of the Indian Ocean, is blessed
with resource base for ecotourism as well as historic and cultural
sites. Tourism is the island country's fourth largest foreign
exchange earner, next to garment, foreign remittances and tea.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Sri Lanka's tourist arrivals hit an all-time high of
436,440, an increase of 14.5 percent over the previous year. The
arrival target for the year 2000 is 535,00 but arrival figures
during the first five months showed a slight decline of 1.5
percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
To increase tourist arrivals, the government is launching a 10
million dollars tourism campaign to sell and promote the country's
varied attractions in the world tourism market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
