<HEADLINE> Shanghai Stock Composite Index Breaks 2,000 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Composite Index at the
Shanghai Stock Exchange hit a new record at 9:30 Wednesday morning,
crossing over the psychological threshold of 2,000 points.
</P>
<P>
Pushed by new listings, the market opened at 2,000:33 points,
according to Homeway, China's leading on-line securities
information provider.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Xiangxue, an analyst with Homeway, said this is an
important landmark for China's stock market.
</P>
<P>
He noted that when the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges
were established in 1990, there were only eight firms listed on
the Shanghai bourse and five on Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Composite Index broke 1,000 points in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Today, there are more than 1,000 listed firms nationwide, and
the market capitalization, totaling 4.4089 trillion yuan,
accounted for 40 percent of China's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said the point of 2,000 is also an important psychological
point for investors, which will further boost investors'
confidence.
</P>
<P>
Analysts, however, reminded that the markets are also faced
with many challenges such as the opening of a second board and the
opening-up of the markets.
</P>
<P>
They warned that investors should be aware of the shortcomings
of China's fledging stock markets, such as poor qualify of listed
firms and the complex structure of equity rights.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
