<HEADLINE> Sichuan University to Train Reserve Army Officers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- A working office on the selection
of reserved army officers has been opened at Sichuan University,
in Chengdu, the capital of Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The working office was set up by the Chengdu Military Area
Command of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA), following
the recent decision by the State Council and the Central Military
Commission to reform the way to foster army officers.
</P>
<P>
Army officers used to be graduates of military schools.
</P>
<P>
The office signed last week an agreement with the university on
the education of 60 reserve officers, who will join the PLA after
their graduation.
</P>
<P>
The 60 were selected from among 300 first- and second-year
students, mostly majoring in electronics, computer science and
mechanics, expertise which is badly needed by the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, each of the students will receive a
subsidy of 5,000 yuan a year. Besides the normal courses at the
school, they will be trained at barracks during vacations.
</P>
<P>
The PLA Chengdu Military Area Command will also cooperate with
other universities in the southwest. In the future, graduates of
senior middle schools could also be selected for the purpose,
according to PLA sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
