<HEADLINE> No Intention to Attack Any Republics: Yugoslav Army Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav army (VJ) has no
intention to attack any republics (in Yugoslavia) because its
mission is to defend them instead of confronting its own people,
an army spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Svetozar Radisic told a press conference that the VJ's
mission is to safeguard Yugoslavia's sovereignty, territorial
integrity and constitutional order.
</P>
<P>
"The army has always been with the people, not against them and
will prevent civil war at any price," said Radisic.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between the republic of Montenegro and the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia have been rising after the Federal Assembly
voted on July 6 for constitutional changes that provide for direct
presidential elections for a four-year mandate, and would allow
the same candidate to stand twice.
</P>
<P>
Currently the president is elected by the chamber of republics
and chamber of citizens in the Federal Assembly for a non-
renewable four-year term.
</P>
<P>
The constitutional changes also allow a direct vote for members
of the chamber of republics. Currently the deputies of the chamber
of republics are voted by each republic's parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Montenegrin parliament rejected the constitutional changes
on the mid-night of July 7, saying that the changes will damage
the interests of the republic of Montenegro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
