<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Welcomes WTO Ruling on Banana Row with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) believed
it won a victory Tuesday in banana trade war over the United
States after the World Trade Organization (WTO) ruled that U.S.
sanctions worth 191 million U.S. dollars were imposed prematurely.
</P>
<P>
"It shows the United States cannot act as judge, jury and
executioners," EU trade spokesman Anthony Gooch said. "That's the
job of the WTO," he added.
</P>
<P>
The United States effectively imposed 100 percent duties on EU
goods in March 1999, about six weeks before the WTO empowered it
to do so.
</P>
<P>
U.S. trade officials said Monday that a WTO panel had backed
the EU, concluding that Washington had no right to act
unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
The WTO had several times ruled the EU's import policy violate
global trade regulations by favoring banana exporters of its
former colonies in the Caribbean, which is mostly marketed by U.S.
giants Chiquita and Dole Foods.
</P>
<P>
Gooch said the European Commission, the EU executive body,
would take no further action itself as a result of the new ruling,
but companies hit by sanctions before the WTO authorization were
now free to take the matter up in U.S. courts to claim damages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
