<HEADLINE> Stamp-collecting Popular in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Stamp-collecting is gaining
popularity in China, with the number of collectors reaching 18
million, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The widely practiced hobby has "not only promoted the expansion
of China's postal service but also contributed to socialist,
cultural and ethical progress of the country", a senior official
of the All-China Philatelic Federation ACPF) was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a three-day national congress of the federation, Luo
Shuzhen, president of ACPF, said that the congress plans to
further advance the stamp-collecting.
</P>
<P>
Some experts even advocated to promote the hobby through
Internet by launching stamp websites where philatelists can
exchange views and their collections, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
Kund Mohr, president of the Federation of International
Philately, said in a letter to the congress that the enthusiasm
towards stamp-collecting in China will greatly contribute to the
development of world stamp-collecting in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
Last August, China successfully hosted the 1999 World
Philatelic Exhibition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Companies Praised for Helping China's Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 19 (Xinhua) -- A group of university students
from this capital of southwestern China's Sichuan Province
launched on July 14 a tree-planting activity in the Aba Tibetan
and Qiang Autonomous Prefecture, Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
This is merely a small part of a major environmental program
titled the "Unilever Living Environment Initiative: Clean Water
and Green Mountains for China" recently initiated by Unilever, a
transnational supplier of daily commodities.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, Unilever plans to spend 35 million yuan to
plant millions of trees across the country, mostly in desert areas,
in five years. This has made the company the largest foreign donor
for tree-planting in China.
</P>
<P>
"All the money must be used for planting trees," said Qu Geping,
a former director of the State Environmental Protection
Administration and now chairman of the Environmental and Resources
Protection Committee of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Qu, who is also president of the Chinese Environmental
Foundation (CEF), spoke highly of transnational companies'
donations for the country's environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Unilever's donation, Qu said it shows that some
foreign companies which have invested in China have begun seeing
the country as their own home. Their activities can be examples
for domestic enterprises and individuals, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Qu also repeatedly mentioned the names of some other foreign
firms that have contributed to China's environmental programs.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese people are grateful to those who have helped China
's environmental protection, and the Chinese government also
appreciates it very much, " he said.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, many foreign companies contacted
the Chinese authorities or the CEF after they learned about
Unilever's donations.
</P>
<P>
Qu urged local companies and individuals to pay greater
attention to environmental protection. "It is far from enough to
rely on government allocations," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, local experts and scholars have urged the
promulgation of relevant laws encouraging companies and
individuals to make donations for environmental purposes. In some
foreign countries, enterprises or individuals enjoy favorable tax
policies if they donate to charitable programs, they noted.
</P>
<P>
With appropriate policies, domestic companies and individuals
may invest more money in environmental protection, Qu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
