<HEADLINE> Fiji's New Cabinet Not to Be Sworn In: Coup Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's coup leader George Speight
has claimed that the country's new cabinet will not be sworn in on
Wednesday as planned following an agreement with President Ratu
Josefa Iloilo to reconsider, Australian TV reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speight said he had not been given the opportunity to have an
input on the make-up of the new cabinet despite an earlier promise
from Iloilo that he would be included in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He told Australia's Channel Nine the president has agreed to
allow him to review the list of prospective ministers on Wednesday
and the planned swearing-in would not proceed.
</P>
<P>
"I have been in touch with the president through a high-ranking
chief of mine to express my disappointment in the fact that that
meeting has not taken place," Speight said.
</P>
<P>
"So in the next hour or so the president will be announcing a
cancellation of the swearing-in ceremony due for 11 a.m. this
morning to enable (us) to speak as he had directed on Monday,"
Speight said.
</P>
<P>
Speight said the proposed administration of 20 ministers and 12
assistant ministers contained only four people supportive of his
May 19 coup against the country's first ethnic Indian prime
minister, Mahendra Chaudhry.
</P>
<P>
It also contains one minister from the large Indian minority
and is headed by Prime Minister Laisenia Qarase, whom Speight had
bitterly opposed when he was appointed interim head of government
by the military earlier this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
