<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Budget Deficit Shrinks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Argentine budget deficit
amounted to 2.238 billion dollars during the first semester of the
year, 451.4 million less than those agreed with the International
Monetary Fund, said the authorities.
</P>
<P>
June was the month with the best budget results, because it
recorded an 874.4 million dollar surplus, a 700 million dollar
improvement compared to the same month of 1999, said the sources
in statements quoted Wednesday by the press.
</P>
<P>
The positive balance compensated the three billion dollar
deficit accumulated in the first five months of the year, and it
was attributed to a 685.5 million dollar increase in tax revenue
and a 14.4 million dollar reduction in expenditures.
</P>
<P>
The expenditures reduction was some 100 million dollars,
distributed among reduction in payments (36.8 million dollars),
real investment (34.9 million dollars), and goods and services (28
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The reduction was compensated by a 75.4 million dollar increase
in interest. The Argentine government expects to achieve this year
the goal of a 4.7 billion dollar deficit agreed with the IMF.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Relief Agencies Warn of Drought Crisis in Central, South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Humanitarian
agencies Wednesday warned that more than 60 million people in
central and south Asia are currently affected by a severe drought,
which has led to rapid deterioration of health conditions,
population displacement and loss of livestock and crops.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Wednesday in New York, the U.N. Inter-
Agency Standing Committee (IASC), bringing together the
organizations with children, refugees, health, food security,
agriculture and relief coordination, said that the drought was
particularly acute in Afghanistan, Tajikistan, Pakistan, Iran and
India.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the press about the IASC's response to the crisis, the
head of the U.N. World Food Program, Cathrine Bertini, said that a
Drought Task Force had been formed to coordinate relief efforts in
the region, and called on the international community to respond
as rapidly as possible.
</P>
<P>
The IASC is also deploying several assessment missions to
evaluate the immediate needs and start planning aid interventions.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's warning follows a previous appeal launched by the U.
N. system in response to the drought crisis in the Middle East, of
which Syria and Jordan were the worst affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
