<HEADLINE> Clinton Struggles to Save Middle East Peace Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Wednesday continued his shuttle mediations between Israelis and
Palestinians, struggling to help them strike a deal at the final
hours of Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who was originally scheduled to leave Wednesday
morning for a summit of industrialized countries in Japan, decided
to postpone his departure by one day for a last ditch effort to
broker a framework agreement between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The president on Wednesday first held bilateral talks with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and then met with Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
The mediation continued amid widespread reports that Barak had
threatened to walk out of the peace talks because the Palestinians
were unwilling to make historic decisions for peace.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman P.J. Crowley confirmed Clinton had
received a letter from Barak but refused to comment its contents.
</P>
<P>
Barak reportedly said in the letter that "To my sorrow, I have
reached the conclusion that the Palestinian side is not conducting
negotiation in good faith and is not prepared to discuss in a
serious fashion achieving a permanent peace between us."
</P>
<P>
Barring last minute developments, he said, "the Palestinians
will witness the tragic consequences of squandering an opportunity.
"
</P>
<P>
It was also reported that Israeli delegates have received
orders to leave Camp David for home sometime Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian sources have refuted Israeli charges, saying that
the talks have come to a crisis because Israel insists on an
undivided sovereignty over Jerusalem, a city both sides claim to
be their capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
