<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Reiterates Firm Support for Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Greece Wednesday repeated its full
support for Cyprus and hoped for a permanent and viable solution
to the island's division problem.
</P>
<P>
Greece was always by the side of Cyprus, Greek President
Costis Stephanopoulos said in a statement on the 26th anniversary
of the Turkish invasion of Cyprus, which has been divided since
1974 when Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third
of the eastern Mediterranean island in the wake of a failed coup
seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Voicing his dissatisfaction over little progress made on the
Cyprus issue, Stephanopoulos said that 26 years after the Turkish
invasion, the Cyprus problem remained unsolved and the illegality
of military occupation was continuing.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that there would be a positive and viable solution to
the Cyprus problem based on the rules of international law and the
U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis said in a
message Wednesday that Greece continued to expect Turkey's
cooperation for a final settlement of the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Describing the Cyprus issue as being at a stage of possible
developments, Simitis said that Greece was moving ahead with
determination and optimism for its solution.
</P>
<P>
The premier stressed that it was in the interest of both
Turkey and the Turkish Cypriots to show appropriate disposition
and to dare those necessary steps for a substantive breakthrough
in talks which had been dragging on for years.
</P>
<P>
To reunite the island, the Greek Cypriot side led President
Glafcos Clerides and the Turkish Cypriot side led by Rauf Denktash
have held two rounds of the U.N.-sponsored proximity talks in New
York and Geneva respectively, and the third round of such talks,
which started in Geneva on July 5 and adjourned for 12 days from
July 12, will be resumed early in August.
</P>
<P>
Greece, which signed a joint defense pact with Nicosia, and
Cyprus have insisted that the island must be reunited in a
federation formula in line with the U.N. resolutions while Turkey
and northern Cyprus demand that a confederation formed by two
sovereign states be set up on the island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
