<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe's Leading Stock Markets End Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Europe's leading stock markets
ended mixed Wednesday, with "old economy" energy and auto stocks
heading higher and technology stocks sinking.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index ended slightly higher helped by a rally
in the oil and gas sector. The blue chip index closed just 14.9
points or 0.23 percent up at 6,465.4.
</P>
<P>
The index added 16 points buoyed by continued high crude prices,
with a 2.8 percent in BP Amoco accounting for most of the rise.
</P>
<P>
Vodafone AirTouch, the index's most heavily weighted stock,
rose 2.6 percent. However, Colt Telecom dropped almost 4 percent
and British telecom lost 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Freight transport company Ocean Group rose 3.6 percent and
cruise ship operator Peninsular and Oriental Steam Navigation Co.
advanced 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Defense and aerospace firm BAE Systems climbed 2.3 percent
after agreeing to sell 10 regional jets to Europe's biggest
airline British Airways.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE Eurotop 300 index, a basket of major companies from
across the region, slipped 0.2 percent to 1,642.76. The
information technology sector fell 1.8 percent while the auto sub
index rose 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt's Xetra Dax index was down 40.34 points, o.5 percent
at 7,366.57 with Europe's leading software firm SAP dropping 2.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 index in Paris slipped 0.2 percent to 6,500.05, with
heavyweight France Telecom and data network operator Equant among
the top decliners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
