<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army not Responsible for Loss of Salaries for Peacekeepers: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan State Minister for Defense
Stephen Kavuma told Parliament that the army is not responsible
for the loss of the 1.6 billion Uganda shillings (about 1 million
U.S. dollars) due to pay Ugandan peacekeepers in the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC), Radio Uganda reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Army officer Dan Byakutaga reportedly obtained the money from
the army headquarters and was expected to fly to the DRC to pay
the country's peacekeepers there. But so far the army has not
established his whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the Members of Parliament (MPs) not to
exaggerate the issue as a committee has already been instituted to
look into the matter, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
It said the MPs rejected Kavuma's statement, urging the
commission of inquiry to probe mismanagement of public funds in
the Ministry of Defense.
</P>
<P>
The MPs further sought the adjournment of the House until the
matter was addressed, said the radio report.
</P>
<P>
But Speaker of Parliament Francis Ayume ruled out the request,
saying it required a substantive motion acceptable to all parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
