<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The South African National
Youth Commission (NYC) said on Thursday that it has identified the
fight against HIV/AIDS, unemployment and skills development as
their key challenges.
</P>
<P>
NYC chairman Jabu Mbalula said in Pretoria that the NYC would
do its utmost to protect the rights and interests of young people
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a function to introduce five new commissioners to
the media, Mbalula said he believed the previous commissioners had
laid a solid foundation and they had to build on it.
</P>
<P>
"We therefore look forward to providing South Africa with
three years of hard work," said Mbalula.
</P>
<P>
Essop Pahad, Minister in the Office of the Presidency,
introduced the five new commissioners to the media -- Mbalula, his
deputy Yoliswa Makhasi, Nketu Matima, Daniel van Vuuren and
Ngwanakopi Rasmushu.
</P>
<P>
The five are the first members of the new-look NYC which was
cut down from 19 commissioners to five in terms of the NYC
Amendment Act.
</P>
<P>
The commission was first inaugurated on June 16, 1996 -- 20
years after hundreds of youths were killed during and immediately
after the Soweto uprising against apartheid. 
