<HEADLINE> U.N. Agency to Cooperate With Nairobi to Ease Water Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Center for
Human Settlement (Habitat) will help the city council of Kenya's
capital Nairobi to find out the exact amount of water used in the
industrial and public sectors in a bid to better manage the water
resources, a senior U.N. official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi city council currently can provide 70 percent of
the water demand, but if the current water crisis persists, the
council will be able to supply only 60 percent to 50 percent of
the demand.
</P>
<P>
The survey on the supply and demand of water resources will
enable the city council to make a reasonable policy for water
management, acting executive director Klaus Toepfer told a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government and the Habitat have been discussing the
way to solve and further avoid the present water crisis, according
to Toepfer.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi-based Habitat is not moving out of Nairobi because
the U.N. agency has chosen to deal with the problem instead of
shirking it, said Toepfer.
</P>
<P>
Last February, the Habitat and the Kenyan government signed a
memorandum of understanding on management of water resources,
which suggests the privatization of water supply as a means to
improve the management of the resource. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
