<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Tries Coup Participants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-five Lesotho Mountain
Police Service members who participated in a mutiny in February
1997 were found guilty on Thursday in the Lesotho High Court of
sedition.
</P>
<P>
Judge Baptista Molai found that the junior officers seized
control of the police headquarters in Maseru and the Maseru
central police station, the South African Press Association
reported.
</P>
<P>
They dismissed the commissioner of police and his deputy and
replaced them with their own men.
</P>
<P>
Twenty three of the accused were found guilty of sedition and
two were convicted of contravening the Internal Security Act,
while three others were discharged.
</P>
<P>
All the accused were cleared of the main charge of high
treason on the grounds that the prosecution had failed to prove
there was any hostile intent among the accused to overthrow the
government or endanger the existence, independence or security of
the state.
</P>
<P>
The court, however, found that the accused found guilty had
participated in unlawful activities against police management over
a period of 10 days, from February 6 until when the mutiny was
crushed by the Lesotho Defense Force on February 16.
</P>
<P>
It was found that the guilty men were in a large group of
junior officers who barricaded themselves in the police
Headquarters and the Maseru central police station and other
police stations.
</P>
<P>
They were armed with rifles and chased away senior officers,"
dismissing" them from the service.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the mutiny, Second Lieutenant Phakiso Molise,
fled to South Africa where he sought political asylum through the
office of the UN High Commissioner for Refugees, but he was later
returned to Lesotho by South African authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
