<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Speaker to Implement Parliamentary Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's newly elected Speaker of
Parliament Emmerson Mnangagwa Thursday said he has set his
priorities on implementing reforms recommended by the
Parliamentary Reform Committee.
</P>
<P>
Mnangagwa told the Zimbabwe News Agency that there are still a
number of reforms to be implemented for the Parliament to operate
more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
"I was part of the last Parliament when some of the reforms
were introduced, so I know where we left," he said. " I will go
through the reforms and implement them," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said people should be allowed to interact more with the
legislative body when the reforms are implemented.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament started to implement the recommendations by its
reform committee last year when it discarded the dress code for
officers inherited from the colonial era.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentarians have been complaining for some time for the
House to uphold the country's culture by phasing out 17th century
wigs and long robes worn by the Speaker's procession.
</P>
<P>
The other recommendations include the publication of the
Hansard, which is in the English language version only, in local
Shona and Ndebele languages.
</P>
<P>
Journalists would be allowed to attend parliamentary committee
meetings which are currently closed to them.
</P>
<P>
The Parliamentary Reform Committee was established in 1997 and
held nationwide consultations to produce its report in May last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
