<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Working out Plans to Boost Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government is
working out, and in some cases has already implemented, strategies
to boost agricultural productivity and diversification, President
Robert Mugabe said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
To further increase small holder farmer productivity, various
measures, including increasing access to land, irrigation
development, input supply and the provision of tillage services
would be put in place and expanded, said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
He told the first session of Zimbabwe's fifth Parliament that
the land resettlement program was being accelerated and it was
envisaged that at least five million hectares of land would be
acquired and developed for resettlement.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe's fiscal deficit has been revised upward to
five percent of the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) because of the
effects of Cyclone Eline.
</P>
<P>
"When the Budget was presented in October last year, the fiscal
deficit was set at 3.8 percent of GDP," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said in the past year the economy has been characterized by
high inflation and interest rates, low foreign currency reserves
and a high budget deficit, among other constraints.
</P>
<P>
He said the Zimbabwe Millennium Economic Recovery Program was
designed to remove the prime causes of inflation and to restore
macro-economic stability so as to create conditions essential for
economic growth and development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
