<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's New Parliament Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's first session of the
Fifth Parliament was opened by President Robert Mugabe on Thursday
with expectations of serious debates because of a strong
opposition since independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
After the swearing-in of the Members of Parliament on Tuesday
and the official opening on Thursday, the new Parliament adjourned
to August 1 when serious business will begin.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, Mugabe touched on a number of issues
affecting the country's economy and promised to withdraw Zimbabwe'
s soldiers from the war-torn Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)
once the United Nations has finished deploying peacekeeping forces.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe's ruling Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front
(Zanu-pf) got 62 seats, the opposition Movement for Democratic
Change (MDC) won 57 seats while Ndabaningi Sithole's Zanu got one
in the parliamentary election on June 24 and 25.
</P>
<P>
A total of 10 chiefs, eight provincial governors and 12 non-
constituency Members of Parliament were also appointed by Mugabe
as legislators. 
</P>
