<HEADLINE> Guatemala, U.S. Sign Anti-Drug Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The governments of the United
States and Guatemala signed Wednesday a new agreement for their
joint war against drug trafficking and related crimes.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed by Guatemalan Foreign Minister
Guillermo Ruiz and U.S. Ambassador in Guatemala Prudence Bushnell,
as reported from Guatemala City.
</P>
<P>
"Our governments (the United States and Guatemala) commit
themselves today to continue supporting the anti-drug programs,"
said the U.S. diplomat.
</P>
<P>
The Guatemalan Legislative Assembly approved in May a bill of
law that permits the entrance of equipment and a limited number of
U.S. military personnel for the war against drug trafficking in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The United States has intensified this year the anti-drug
cooperation with Guatemala, a country considered as a territory of
transit for the drugs targeted to the U.S. market, the most avid
for drugs in the world.
</P>
<P>
Cocaine seized in Guatemala this year amounted to three tons,
while it was 10 tons in 1999. 
