<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fischer: European Federation, Decade-Long Task </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Joschka
Fischer said that the building of The European Union into a more
tightly-knit European Federation should be put in a "decade
perspective."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to German media recently, Fischer said that the
widening of the EU, the strengthening of euro and the trend of
globalization call for such a federation, the German news agency
DPA reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Without a political union, which consists of a full parliament,
an executive branch and a "clear constitutional relationship," the
EU members would fall in "self-blockade" and a "deep crisis," he
said.
</P>
<P>
But he explained that the so-called European Federation is not
the United States of Europe, but a "union of nation-states, which
exercise part of their sovereignty in joint institutions" and "at
the same time with a strong role also for the nation-states."
</P>
<P>
Fischer stirred a strong reaction both at home and abroad two
months ago, when he called in a speech at Berlin's Humboldt
University for the establishment of a European Federation with a
two-chamber parliament and a directly-elected president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
