<HEADLINE> Argentine Police Repress Workers Demonstration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Police repressed with rubber
bullets and tear gas sugar industry workers who demonstrated
Wednesday in front of the Savings Bank in the Argentine city of
Tucuman to demand credits.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said that the incident that lasted 15 minutes
started when the demonstrators, led by Anibal Ibarra, general
secretary of the Sugar Industry Workers Federation, entered the
Independencia Plaza in the city. There were no victims.
</P>
<P>
Police Chief of the Tucuman province Alberto Alcaraz said that
they will not listen to the protests if projectiles are thrown
with slingshots, sticks are used to cause damage and car tires are
burned to disrupt the public order.
</P>
<P>
The workers denied having carried firearms to enter the plaza
to stage their demonstration against the government, and accused
police of setting up a trap, and that they expect to talk with the
provincial authorities. 
