<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Facing Challenge: OECD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD) said Wednesday that Mexico
faces the challenge of a strong sustainable growth in the long
term after the upcoming change of government.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's economic development will be favorable in the short
term, with an average annual expansion of 5 percent, said the OECD
in a report on the Latin American country, according to a report
reaching here from Paris.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of Mexico's foreign trade was made last year
with the United States, its biggest trade partner.
</P>
<P>
The OECD, of which Mexico is one of its 29 members, said that
the Latin American country's finances are nearly balanced, its
inflation is diminishing, and its current account deficit is
moderate.
</P>
<P>
The OECD recommended a bigger tax revenue because "the relative
lack of tax income and the strong dependence on oil profits are
important obstacles for the development of essential public
programs."
</P>
<P>
The organization forecast a 4.5 to 5 percent growth for Mexico
this year and the next, and an inflation drop to 7.5 percent in
2000 if there are no rate of exchange unexpected shocks.
</P>
<P>
Mexican President-elect Vicente Fox, who will take office on
December 1, said his government will promote a 7 percent annual
growth and that it will try to expand the taxable mass by
promoting micro and small enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Mexico (central bank) said that the country will
close 2000 with a 9.2 percent inflation that will reduce to 3
percent in 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000719.0352 </DOCNO>
