<P>
The technology heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 121.54 at 4,
055.63. The composite lost 97.50 points in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index fell 11.78 at 1,481.96.
</P>
<P>
Stocks fell as Commence One, an e-commerce software company,
and Veritas Software Corp., maker of data storage-management
software, reported separately that their second quarter losses
were greater than a year ago. The shares of the two Internet
companies fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
Investors also dumped Microsoft's shares after the software
giant reported later Tuesday that the company's earnings in the
second quarter were better than expected but sales in the quarter
were stagnant, about equal to the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The selloff in the tech sector spread to the whole market
despite the positive earnings report from Citigroup. The financial
company said that its earnings in the second quarter rose 23
percent over the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Investors' uncertainty about interest rates also had an effect
on the market before Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan makes
testimony before a Senate committee Thursday. Investors expected
Greenspan to tell the lawmakers about the slowdown in the U.S.
economy after six hikes in rates but they did not know whether the
slowdown will end the year-long cycle of monetary tightening.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 1.26 at 656.95 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 6.59 at 937.16. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 8.42 at 537.86.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,699 down, 1,114 up and 555
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 902.76 million shares from 905.33
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
