<HEADLINE> U.S. Sprayed Defoliating Fungus in Ecuador: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Guayaquil College of Agronomist
Engineers said Wednesday that the United States has used spores of
the Fusarium oxysporum fungus in Ecuador in spite of the denial of
the two governments.
</P>
<P>
College president Roboan Gavilanes said that its members are
certain that this fungus has been used in the Ecuadoran Amazon
region.
</P>
<P>
Gavilanes said that this substance has been applied in the east
of Ecuador under the pretext of destroying coca plant cultivations.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Guayaquil agronomist engineers are willing to
determine, together with the press, the site where the spores of
the fungus were applied, as an experimental dress rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
One of the characteristics of the fungus is to migrate easily
and that there will be no way to reduce the affected zones since,
according to the direction of the wind and the strength of the
lethal fungus, it could affect the agriculture sectors of the
Costa and Sierra of Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
The New Herald Miami newspaper said Monday that U.S.
technicians sprayed the Fusarium Oxysporum fungus spores in the
eastern Ecuadoran province of Sucumbios to eradicate coca cultives.
However, Ecuador and the United States denied the accusation.
</P>
<P>
Local experts said that the use of that fungus would produce
serious damage to the environment and people because the
microtoxins produced by this agent are toxic, and so the Fusarium
oxysporum can be considered a biological weapon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
