<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi's Major Rebel Group Committed to Rebuilding Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Burundi's major armed rebel
group said on Thursday it is committed to the restoration of peace
in Burundi, but fell short to state clearly whether they will sign
the rescheduled peace agreement on August 28.
</P>
<P>
Jean Bosco Ndayikengurukiye, leader of the National Council
for the Defense of Democracy -- Forces for the Defense of
Democracy (CNDD-FDD), said his movement wants to see peace arrive
in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the group will only stop the armed
struggle if there is full restoration of human rights and
democracy in the country.
</P>
<P>
Ndayikengurukiye made these remarks at his maiden press
conference in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha where another
round of Burundi peace talks is being held under the mediation of
former South African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
He said he came to demonstrate that they want peace, adding
that they had a lot to contribute in the draft peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
This has been the first time for the leader of the majority
Hutu rebel group to attend the talks since they started two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft accord, the Tutsi minority, which has dominated
Burundi's political and economic life since independence, will
have to hand over power to a democratically elected government
within three years.
</P>
<P>
Ndayikengurukiye reiterated that at present main concern of his
group is the immediate dismantling of the resettlement camps for
Hutus, which were set up by the Burundian government to cut them
off from anti-government rebels, and the release of all political
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Burundian President Pierre Buyoya has agreed to close the camps
by the end of this month, but many parties doubt his good faith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
