<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Trys to Recover Forest Vegetation in Southern Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian environmental
authorities are taking measures to recover in southern Bale and
Borena regions green vegetation destroyed by wildfire early this
year, an official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Duro Bulbula, chief of the Oromiya Wildlife and Forestry
Protection Department, said that 135 million seedlings have been
nurtured for transplantation on lands ravaged by wild fire rampant
between late February and early April.
</P>
<P>
Duro said that the transplantation has already started in
Borena and Bale regions where some 14 million seedlings have been
transplanted since late June.
</P>
<P>
When the transplantation work is completed, a total of 15,000
hectares of land will be covered by trees, he said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that of the 580,000 hectares of forest in Bale
and Borean regions, 70,000 hectares were burned to ashes in the
bushfires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
